  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David in His Old Age'
      title: David in His Old Age
      number: 1
      content: '  King David was now very old, and no matter how many blankets covered
        him, he could not keep warm. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So his advisers told him, \u201CLet us find a young virgin to wait
        on you and look after you, my lord. She will lie in your arms and keep you
        warm.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So they searched throughout the land of Israel for a beautiful girl,
        and they found Abishag from Shunem and brought her to the king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: Adonijah Claims the Throne'
      title: Adonijah Claims the Throne
      number: 4
      content: 'The girl was very beautiful, and she looked after the king and took
        care of him. But the king had no sexual relations with her.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "About that time David\u2019s son Adonijah, whose mother was Haggith,
        began boasting, \u201CI will make myself king.\u201D So he provided himself
        with chariots and charioteers and recruited fifty men to run in front of
        him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Now his father, King David, had never disciplined him at any time,
        even by asking, \u201CWhy are you doing that?\u201D Adonijah had been born
        next after Absalom, and he was very handsome.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Adonijah took Joab son of Zeruiah and Abiathar the priest into his
        confidence, and they agreed to help him become king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But Zadok the priest, Benaiah son of Jehoiada, Nathan the prophet,
        Shimei, Rei, and David\u2019s personal bodyguard refused to support Adonijah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Adonijah went to the Stone of Zoheleth[[COMMENT(0)]] near the spring
        of En-rogel, where he sacrificed sheep, cattle, and fattened calves. He invited
        all his brothers\u2014the other sons of King David\u2014and all the royal
        officials of Judah. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:9 '
        content: "Or <b>to the Serpent\u2019s Stone; </b>Greek version supports reading
          <b>Zoheleth </b>as a proper name."
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But he did not invite Nathan the prophet or Benaiah or the king\u2019s
        bodyguard or his brother Solomon.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then Nathan went to Bathsheba, Solomon\u2019s mother, and asked her,
        \u201CHaven\u2019t you heard that Haggith\u2019s son, Adonijah, has made
        himself king, and our lord David doesn\u2019t even know about it? "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'If you want to save your own life and the life of your son Solomon,
        follow my advice. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Go at once to King David and say to him, \u2018My lord the king,
        didn\u2019t you make a vow and say to me, \u201CYour son Solomon will surely
        be the next king and will sit on my throne\u201D? Why then has Adonijah become
        king?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "And while you are still talking with him, I will come and confirm
        everything you have said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "So Bathsheba went into the king\u2019s bedroom. (He was very old
        now, and Abishag was taking care of him.) "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Bathsheba bowed down before the king.\u201CWhat can I do for you?\u201D
        he asked her.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "She replied, \u201CMy lord, you made a vow before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God when you said to me, \u2018Your son Solomon will surely be the next
        king and will sit on my throne.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'But instead, Adonijah has made himself king, and my lord the king
        does not even know about it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He has sacrificed many cattle, fattened calves, and sheep, and he
        has invited all the king\u2019s sons to attend the celebration. He also invited
        Abiathar the priest and Joab, the commander of the army. But he did not invite
        your servant Solomon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'And now, my lord the king, all Israel is waiting for you to announce
        who will become king after you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "If you do not act, my son Solomon and I will be treated as criminals
        as soon as my lord the king has died.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'While she was still speaking with the king, Nathan the prophet arrived. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "The king\u2019s officials told him, \u201CNathan the prophet is here
        to see you.\u201DNathan went in and bowed before the king with his face to
        the ground. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Nathan asked, \u201CMy lord the king, have you decided that Adonijah
        will be the next king and that he will sit on your throne? "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Today he has sacrificed many cattle, fattened calves, and sheep,
        and he has invited all the king\u2019s sons to attend the celebration. He
        also invited the commanders of the army and Abiathar the priest. They are
        feasting and drinking with him and shouting, \u2018Long live King Adonijah!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'But he did not invite me or Zadok the priest or Benaiah or your servant
        Solomon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: David Makes Solomon King'
      title: David Makes Solomon King
      number: 27
      content: "Has my lord the king really done this without letting any of his
        officials know who should be the next king?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "King David responded, \u201CCall Bathsheba!\u201D So she came back
        in and stood before the king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "And the king repeated his vow: \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives, who has rescued me from every danger, "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "your son Solomon will be the next king and will sit on my throne
        this very day, just as I vowed to you before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then Bathsheba bowed down with her face to the ground before the
        king and exclaimed, \u201CMay my lord King David live forever!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Then King David ordered, \u201CCall Zadok the priest, Nathan the
        prophet, and Benaiah son of Jehoiada.\u201D When they came into the king\u2019s
        presence, "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "the king said to them, \u201CTake Solomon and my officials down to
        Gihon Spring. Solomon is to ride on my own mule. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "There Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet are to anoint him king
        over Israel. Blow the ram\u2019s horn and shout, \u2018Long live King Solomon!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Then escort him back here, and he will sit on my throne. He will
        succeed me as king, for I have appointed him to be ruler over Israel and
        Judah.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CAmen!\u201D Benaiah son of Jehoiada replied. \u201CMay the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of my lord the king, decree that it
        happen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "And may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> be with Solomon as he has
        been with you, my lord the king, and may he make Solomon\u2019s reign even
        greater than yours!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "So Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, Benaiah son of Jehoiada,
        and the king\u2019s bodyguard[[COMMENT(0)]] took Solomon down to Gihon Spring,
        with Solomon riding on King David\u2019s own mule. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:38 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Kerethites and Pelethites; </b>also in 1:44.
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "There Zadok the priest took the flask of olive oil from the sacred
        tent and anointed Solomon with the oil. Then they sounded the ram\u2019s
        horn and all the people shouted, \u201CLong live King Solomon!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'And all the people followed Solomon into Jerusalem, playing flutes
        and shouting for joy. The celebration was so joyous and noisy that the earth
        shook with the sound.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Adonijah and his guests heard the celebrating and shouting just as
        they were finishing their banquet. When Joab heard the sound of the ram\u2019s
        horn, he asked, \u201CWhat\u2019s going on? Why is the city in such an uproar?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "And while he was still speaking, Jonathan son of Abiathar the priest
        arrived. \u201CCome in,\u201D Adonijah said to him, \u201Cfor you are a good
        man. You must have good news.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "\u201CNot at all!\u201D Jonathan replied. \u201COur lord King David
        has just declared Solomon king! "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "The king sent him down to Gihon Spring with Zadok the priest, Nathan
        the prophet, and Benaiah son of Jehoiada, protected by the king\u2019s bodyguard.
        They had him ride on the king\u2019s own mule, "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "and Zadok and Nathan have anointed him at Gihon Spring as the new
        king. They have just returned, and the whole city is celebrating and rejoicing.
        That\u2019s what all the noise is about. "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "What\u2019s more, Solomon is now sitting on the royal throne as king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "And all the royal officials have gone to King David and congratulated
        him, saying, \u2018May your God make Solomon\u2019s fame even greater than
        your own, and may Solomon\u2019s reign be even greater than yours!\u2019
        Then the king bowed his head in worship as he lay in his bed, "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "and he said, \u2018Praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel, who today has chosen a successor to sit on my throne while I am
        still alive to see it.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "Then all of Adonijah\u2019s guests jumped up in panic from the banquet
        table and quickly scattered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'Adonijah was afraid of Solomon, so he rushed to the sacred tent and
        grabbed on to the horns of the altar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "Word soon reached Solomon that Adonijah had seized the horns of the
        altar in fear, and that he was pleading, \u201CLet King Solomon swear today
        that he will not kill me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "Solomon replied, \u201CIf he proves himself to be loyal, not a hair
        on his head will be touched. But if he makes trouble, he will die.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: "So King Solomon summoned Adonijah, and they brought him down from
        the altar. He came and bowed respectfully before King Solomon, who dismissed
        him, saying, \u201CGo on home.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Final Instructions to Solomon"
      title: "David\u2019s Final Instructions to Solomon"
      number: 1
      content: "  As the time of King David\u2019s death approached, he gave this
        charge to his son Solomon:  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CI am going where everyone on earth must someday go. Take courage
        and be a man. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Observe the requirements of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God, and follow all his ways. Keep the decrees, commands, regulations, and
        laws written in the Law of Moses so that you will be successful in all you
        do and wherever you go. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "If you do this, then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will keep the
        promise he made to me. He told me, \u2018If your descendants live as they
        should and follow me faithfully with all their heart and soul, one of them
        will always sit on the throne of Israel.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CAnd there is something else. You know what Joab son of Zeruiah
        did to me when he murdered my two army commanders, Abner son of Ner and Amasa
        son of Jether. He pretended that it was an act of war, but it was done in
        a time of peace,[[COMMENT(0)]] staining his belt and sandals with innocent
        blood.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:5a '
        content: Or <b>He murdered them during a time of peace as revenge for deaths
          they had caused in time of war.</b>
      - number: '2:5b '
        content: As in some Greek and Old Latin manuscripts; Hebrew reads <b>with
          the blood of war.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Do with him what you think best, but don\u2019t let him grow old
        and go to his grave in peace.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:6 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>don\u2019t let his white head go down to Sheol in peace.</b>"
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CBe kind to the sons of Barzillai of Gilead. Make them permanent
        guests at your table, for they took care of me when I fled from your brother
        Absalom.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CAnd remember Shimei son of Gera, the man from Bahurim in Benjamin.
        He cursed me with a terrible curse as I was fleeing to Mahanaim. When he
        came down to meet me at the Jordan River, I swore by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that I would not kill him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But that oath does not make him innocent. You are a wise man, and
        you will know how to arrange a bloody death for him.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>how to bring his white head down to Sheol in blood.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then David died and was buried with his ancestors in the City of
        David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'David had reigned over Israel for forty years, seven of them in Hebron
        and thirty-three in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Solomon Establishes His Rule'
      title: Solomon Establishes His Rule
      number: 12
      content: 'Solomon became king and sat on the throne of David his father, and
        his kingdom was firmly established.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "One day Adonijah, whose mother was Haggith, came to see Bathsheba,
        Solomon\u2019s mother. \u201CHave you come with peaceful intentions?\u201D
        she asked him.\u201CYes,\u201D he said, \u201CI come in peace. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "In fact, I have a favor to ask of you.\u201D\u201CWhat is it?\u201D
        she asked.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "He replied, \u201CAs you know, the kingdom was rightfully mine; all
        Israel wanted me to be the next king. But the tables were turned, and the
        kingdom went to my brother instead; for that is the way the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        wanted it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So now I have just one favor to ask of you. Please don\u2019t turn
        me down.\u201D\u201CWhat is it?\u201D she asked.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He replied, \u201CSpeak to King Solomon on my behalf, for I know
        he will do anything you request. Ask him to let me marry Abishag, the girl
        from Shunem.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Bathsheba replied. \u201CI will speak to the
        king for you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "So Bathsheba went to King Solomon to speak on Adonijah\u2019s behalf.
        The king rose from his throne to meet her, and he bowed down before her.
        When he sat down on his throne again, the king ordered that a throne be brought
        for his mother, and she sat at his right hand.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CI have one small request to make of you,\u201D she said. \u201CI
        hope you won\u2019t turn me down.\u201D\u201CWhat is it, my mother?\u201D
        he asked. \u201CYou know I won\u2019t refuse you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThen let your brother Adonijah marry Abishag, the girl from
        Shunem,\u201D she replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CHow can you possibly ask me to give Abishag to Adonijah?\u201D
        King Solomon demanded. \u201CYou might as well ask me to give him the kingdom!
        You know that he is my older brother, and that he has Abiathar the priest
        and Joab son of Zeruiah on his side.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then King Solomon made a vow before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        \u201CMay God strike me and even kill me if Adonijah has not sealed his fate
        with this request. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has confirmed me and placed me on
        the throne of my father, David; he has established my dynasty as he promised.
        So as surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives, Adonijah will die
        this very day!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'So King Solomon ordered Benaiah son of Jehoiada to execute him, and
        Adonijah was put to death.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then the king said to Abiathar the priest, \u201CGo back to your
        home in Anathoth. You deserve to die, but I will not kill you now, because
        you carried the Ark of the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for David
        my father and you shared all his hardships.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'So Solomon deposed Abiathar from his position as priest of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        thereby fulfilling the prophecy the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given
        at Shiloh concerning the descendants of Eli.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Joab had not joined Absalom\u2019s earlier rebellion, but he had
        joined Adonijah\u2019s rebellion. So when Joab heard about Adonijah\u2019s
        death, he ran to the sacred tent of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and grabbed
        on to the horns of the altar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'When this was reported to King Solomon, he sent Benaiah son of Jehoiada
        to execute him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Benaiah went to the sacred tent of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and said to Joab, \u201CThe king orders you to come out!\u201DBut Joab answered,
        \u201CNo, I will die here.\u201DSo Benaiah returned to the king and told
        him what Joab had said.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CDo as he said,\u201D the king replied. \u201CKill him there
        beside the altar and bury him. This will remove the guilt of Joab\u2019s
        senseless murders from me and from my father\u2019s family. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will repay him[[COMMENT(0)]] for
        the murders of two men who were more righteous and better than he. For my
        father knew nothing about the deaths of Abner son of Ner, commander of the
        army of Israel, and of Amasa son of Jether, commander of the army of Judah. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>will return his blood on his own head.</b>
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "May their blood be on Joab and his descendants forever, and may the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> grant peace forever to David, his descendants,
        his dynasty, and his throne.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'So Benaiah son of Jehoiada returned to the sacred tent and killed
        Joab, and he was buried at his home in the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Then the king appointed Benaiah to command the army in place of Joab,
        and he installed Zadok the priest to take the place of Abiathar.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "The king then sent for Shimei and told him, \u201CBuild a house here
        in Jerusalem and live there. But don\u2019t step outside the city to go anywhere
        else. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "On the day you so much as cross the Kidron Valley, you will surely
        die; and your blood will be on your own head.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Shimei replied, \u201CYour sentence is fair; I will do whatever my
        lord the king commands.\u201D So Shimei lived in Jerusalem for a long time.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "But three years later two of Shimei\u2019s slaves ran away to King
        Achish son of Maacah of Gath. When Shimei learned where they were, "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'he saddled his donkey and went to Gath to search for them. When he
        found them, he brought them back to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'Solomon heard that Shimei had left Jerusalem and had gone to Gath
        and returned. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "So the king sent for Shimei and demanded, \u201CDidn\u2019t I make
        you swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and warn you not to go anywhere
        else or you would surely die? And you replied, \u2018The sentence is fair;
        I will do as you say.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Then why haven\u2019t you kept your oath to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and obeyed my command?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "The king also said to Shimei, \u201CYou certainly remember all the
        wicked things you did to my father, David. May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        now bring that evil on your own head. "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "But may I, King Solomon, receive the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        blessings, and may one of David\u2019s descendants always sit on this throne
        in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Then, at the king\u2019s command, Benaiah son of Jehoiada took Shimei
        outside and killed him.So the kingdom was now firmly in Solomon\u2019s grip."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Asks for Wisdom'
      title: Solomon Asks for Wisdom
      number: 1
      content: '  Solomon made an alliance with Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, and married
        one of his daughters. He brought her to live in the City of David until he
        could finish building his palace and the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and the wall around the city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'At that time the people of Israel sacrificed their offerings at local
        places of worship, for a temple honoring the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had not yet been built.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Solomon loved the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and followed all the
        decrees of his father, David, except that Solomon, too, offered sacrifices
        and burned incense at the local places of worship. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The most important of these places of worship was at Gibeon, so the
        king went there and sacrificed 1,000 burnt offerings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "That night the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to Solomon in
        a dream, and God said, \u201CWhat do you want? Ask, and I will give it to
        you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Solomon replied, \u201CYou showed great and faithful love to your
        servant my father, David, because he was honest and true and faithful to
        you. And you have continued to show this great and faithful love to him today
        by giving him a son to sit on his throne.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CNow, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God, you have made me
        king instead of my father, David, but I am like a little child who doesn\u2019t
        know his way around. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'And here I am in the midst of your own chosen people, a nation so
        great and numerous they cannot be counted! '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Give me an understanding heart so that I can govern your people well
        and know the difference between right and wrong. For who by himself is able
        to govern this great people of yours?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'The Lord was pleased that Solomon had asked for wisdom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "So God replied, \u201CBecause you have asked for wisdom in governing
        my people with justice and have not asked for a long life or wealth or the
        death of your enemies\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I will give you what you asked for! I will give you a wise and understanding
        heart such as no one else has had or ever will have! '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And I will also give you what you did not ask for\u2014riches and
        fame! No other king in all the world will be compared to you for the rest
        of your life! "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "And if you follow me and obey my decrees and my commands as your
        father, David, did, I will give you a long life.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: Solomon Judges Wisely'
      title: Solomon Judges Wisely
      number: 15
      content: "Then Solomon woke up and realized it had been a dream. He returned
        to Jerusalem and stood before the Ark of the Lord\u2019s Covenant, where
        he sacrificed burnt offerings and peace offerings. Then he invited all his
        officials to a great banquet.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Some time later two prostitutes came to the king to have an argument
        settled. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CPlease, my lord,\u201D one of them began, \u201Cthis woman
        and I live in the same house. I gave birth to a baby while she was with me
        in the house. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Three days later this woman also had a baby. We were alone; there
        were only two of us in the house.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CBut her baby died during the night when she rolled over on
        it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then she got up in the night and took my son from beside me while
        I was asleep. She laid her dead child in my arms and took mine to sleep beside
        her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "And in the morning when I tried to nurse my son, he was dead! But
        when I looked more closely in the morning light, I saw that it wasn\u2019t
        my son at all.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then the other woman interrupted, \u201CIt certainly was your son,
        and the living child is mine.\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D the first woman said,
        \u201Cthe living child is mine, and the dead one is yours.\u201D And so they
        argued back and forth before the king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then the king said, \u201CLet\u2019s get the facts straight. Both
        of you claim the living child is yours, and each says that the dead one belongs
        to the other. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "All right, bring me a sword.\u201D So a sword was brought to the
        king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then he said, \u201CCut the living child in two, and give half to
        one woman and half to the other!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then the woman who was the real mother of the living child, and who
        loved him very much, cried out, \u201COh no, my lord! Give her the child\u2014please
        do not kill him!\u201DBut the other woman said, \u201CAll right, he will
        be neither yours nor mine; divide him between us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then the king said, \u201CDo not kill the child, but give him to
        the woman who wants him to live, for she is his mother!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "When all Israel heard the king\u2019s decision, the people were in
        awe of the king, for they saw the wisdom God had given him for rendering
        justice."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Solomon\u2019s Officials and Governors"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Officials and Governors"
      number: 1
      content: '  King Solomon now ruled over all Israel, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'and these were his high officials:Azariah son of Zadok was the priest.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Elihoreph and Ahijah, the sons of Shisha, were court secretaries.Jehoshaphat
        son of Ahilud was the royal historian.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Benaiah son of Jehoiada was commander of the army.Zadok and Abiathar
        were priests.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Azariah son of Nathan was in charge of the district governors.Zabud
        son of Nathan, a priest, was a trusted adviser to the king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Ahishar was manager of the palace property.Adoniram son of Abda was
        in charge of forced labor.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Solomon also had twelve district governors who were over all Israel.
        They were responsible for providing food for the king\u2019s household. Each
        of them arranged provisions for one month of the year. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'These are the names of the twelve governors:Ben-hur, in the hill
        country of Ephraim.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Ben-deker, in Makaz, Shaalbim, Beth-shemesh, and Elon-bethhanan.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Ben-hesed, in Arubboth, including Socoh and all the land of Hepher.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Ben-abinadab, in all of Naphoth-dor.[[COMMENT(0)]] (He was married
        to Taphath, one of Solomon\u2019s daughters.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Naphath-dor, </b>a variant spelling of Naphoth-dor.
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Baana son of Ahilud, in Taanach and Megiddo, all of Beth-shan[[COMMENT(0)]]
        near Zarethan below Jezreel, and all the territory from Beth-shan to Abel-meholah
        and over to Jokmeam.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Beth-shean, </b>a variant spelling of Beth-shan; also
          in 4:12b.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Ben-geber, in Ramoth-gilead, including the Towns of Jair (named for
        Jair of the tribe of Manasseh[[COMMENT(0)]]) in Gilead, and in the Argob
        region of Bashan, including sixty large fortified towns with bronze bars
        on their gates.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jair son of Manasseh; </b>compare 1 Chr 2:22.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Ahinadab son of Iddo, in Mahanaim.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Ahimaaz, in Naphtali. (He was married to Basemath, another of Solomon\u2019s
        daughters.)  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Baana son of Hushai, in Asher and in Aloth.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Jehoshaphat son of Paruah, in Issachar.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Shimei son of Ela, in Benjamin.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "19: Solomon\u2019s Prosperity and Wisdom"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Prosperity and Wisdom"
      number: 19
      content: 'Geber son of Uri, in the land of Gilead,[[COMMENT(0)]] including
        the territories of King Sihon of the Amorites and King Og of Bashan.There
        was also one governor over the land of Judah.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:19a '
        content: Greek version reads <b>of Gad; </b>compare 4:13.
      - number: '4:19b '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts; Hebrew lacks <b>of Judah. </b>The
          meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The people of Judah and Israel were as numerous as the sand on the
        seashore. They were very contented, with plenty to eat and drink. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: '[[COMMENT(0)]]Solomon ruled over all the kingdoms from the Euphrates
        River[[COMMENT(1)]] in the north to the land of the Philistines and the border
        of Egypt in the south. The conquered peoples of those lands sent tribute
        money to Solomon and continued to serve him throughout his lifetime.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:21a '
        content: Verses 4:21-34 are numbered 5:1-14 in Hebrew text.
      - number: '4:21b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river; </b>also in 4:24.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The daily food requirements for Solomon\u2019s palace were 150 bushels
        of choice flour and 300 bushels of meal[[COMMENT(0)]]; "
      comments:
      - number: '4:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>30 cors </b>[6.6 kiloliters] <b>of choice flour and 60
          cors </b>[13.2 kiloliters] <b>of meal.</b>
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'also 10 oxen from the fattening pens, 20 pasture-fed cattle, 100
        sheep or goats, as well as deer, gazelles, roe deer, and choice poultry.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:23 '
        content: Or <b>and fattened geese.</b>
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Solomon\u2019s dominion extended over all the kingdoms west of the
        Euphrates River, from Tiphsah to Gaza. And there was peace on all his borders. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'During the lifetime of Solomon, all of Judah and Israel lived in
        peace and safety. And from Dan in the north to Beersheba in the south, each
        family had its own home and garden.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>each family lived under its own grapevine and under its
          own fig tree.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Solomon had 4,000[[COMMENT(0)]] stalls for his chariot horses, and
        he had 12,000 horses.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:26a '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 2 Chr 9:25); Hebrew reads
          <b>40,000.</b>
      - number: '4:26b '
        content: Or <b>12,000 charioteers.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'The district governors faithfully provided food for King Solomon
        and his court; each made sure nothing was lacking during the month assigned
        to him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They also brought the necessary barley and straw for the royal horses
        in the stables.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'God gave Solomon very great wisdom and understanding, and knowledge
        as vast as the sands of the seashore. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'In fact, his wisdom exceeded that of all the wise men of the East
        and the wise men of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He was wiser than anyone else, including Ethan the Ezrahite and the
        sons of Mahol\u2014Heman, Calcol, and Darda. His fame spread throughout all
        the surrounding nations. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'He composed some 3,000 proverbs and wrote 1,005 songs. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'He could speak with authority about all kinds of plants, from the
        great cedar of Lebanon to the tiny hyssop that grows from cracks in a wall.
        He could also speak about animals, birds, small creatures, and fish. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: And kings from every nation sent their ambassadors to listen to the
        wisdom of Solomon.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Preparations for Building the Temple'
      title: Preparations for Building the Temple
      number: 1
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]King Hiram of Tyre had always been a loyal friend
        of David. When Hiram learned that David\u2019s son Solomon was the new king
        of Israel, he sent ambassadors to congratulate him.  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:1 '
        content: '  Verses 5:1-18 are numbered 5:15-32 in Hebrew text.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then Solomon sent this message back to Hiram:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CYou know that my father, David, was not able to build a Temple
        to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God because of the
        many wars waged against him by surrounding nations. He could not build until
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave him victory over all his enemies. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God has given me peace
        on every side; I have no enemies, and all is well. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So I am planning to build a Temple to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God, just as he had instructed my father, David. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him, \u2018Your son, whom I will place on your throne, will build the
        Temple to honor my name.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CTherefore, please command that cedars from Lebanon be cut for
        me. Let my men work alongside yours, and I will pay your men whatever wages
        you ask. As you know, there is no one among us who can cut timber like you
        Sidonians!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "When Hiram received Solomon\u2019s message, he was very pleased and
        said, \u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> today for giving David
        a wise son to be king of the great nation of Israel.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then he sent this reply to Solomon:\u201CI have received your message,
        and I will supply all the cedar and cypress timber you need. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "My servants will bring the logs from the Lebanon mountains to the
        Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] and make them into rafts and float them along
        the coast to whatever place you choose. Then we will break the rafts apart
        so you can carry the logs away. You can pay me by supplying me with food
        for my household.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So Hiram supplied as much cedar and cypress timber as Solomon desired. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'In return, Solomon sent him an annual payment of 100,000 bushels[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of wheat for his household and 110,000 gallons[[COMMENT(1)]] of pure olive
        oil. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>20,000 cors </b>[4,400 kiloliters].
      - number: '5:11b '
        content: As in Greek version, which reads <b>20,000 baths </b>[420 kiloliters]
          (see also 2 Chr 2:10); Hebrew reads <b>20 cors, </b>about 1,000 gallons
          or 4.4 kiloliters in volume.
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave wisdom to Solomon, just as
        he had promised. And Hiram and Solomon made a formal alliance of peace.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then King Solomon conscripted a labor force of 30,000 men from all
        Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'He sent them to Lebanon in shifts, 10,000 every month, so that each
        man would be one month in Lebanon and two months at home. Adoniram was in
        charge of this labor force. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Solomon also had 70,000 common laborers, 80,000 quarry workers in
        the hill country, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'and 3,600[[COMMENT(0)]] foremen to supervise the work. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:16 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 2 Chr 2:2, 18); Hebrew reads
          <b>3,300.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "At the king\u2019s command, they quarried large blocks of high-quality
        stone and shaped them to make the foundation of the Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Men from the city of Gebal helped Solomon\u2019s and Hiram\u2019s
        builders prepare the timber and stone for the Temple."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Builds the Temple'
      title: Solomon Builds the Temple
      number: 1
      content: "  It was in midspring, in the month of Ziv,[[COMMENT(0)]] during
        the fourth year of Solomon\u2019s reign, that he began to construct the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. This was 480 years after the people of
        Israel were rescued from their slavery in the land of Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>It was in the month of Ziv, which is the second month.
          </b>This month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within
          the months of April and May.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The Temple that King Solomon built for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was 90 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 45 feet high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>60 cubits </b>[27.6 meters] <b>long, 20 cubits </b>[9.2
          meters] <b>wide, and 30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The entry room at the front of the Temple was 30 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide, running across the entire width of the Temple. It projected outward
        15 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] from the front of the Temple. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:3a '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[9.2 meters]; also in 6:16, 20.
      - number: '6:3b '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters].
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Solomon also made narrow recessed windows throughout the Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He built a complex of rooms against the outer walls of the Temple,
        all the way around the sides and rear of the building. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The complex was three stories high, the bottom floor being 7-1/2
        feet wide, the second floor 9 feet wide, and the top floor 10-1/2 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        The rooms were connected to the walls of the Temple by beams resting on ledges
        built out from the wall. So the beams were not inserted into the walls themselves.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the bottom floor being 5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters] <b>wide,
          the second floor 6 cubits </b>[2.8 meters] <b>wide, and the top floor 7
          cubits </b>[3.2 meters] <b>wide</b>.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The stones used in the construction of the Temple were finished at
        the quarry, so there was no sound of hammer, ax, or any other iron tool at
        the building site.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The entrance to the bottom floor[[COMMENT(0)]] was on the south side
        of the Temple. There were winding stairs going up to the second floor, and
        another flight of stairs between the second and third floors. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:8 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>middle floor.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'After completing the Temple structure, Solomon put in a ceiling made
        of cedar beams and planks. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'As already stated, he built a complex of rooms along the sides of
        the building, attached to the Temple walls by cedar timbers. Each story of
        the complex was 7-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] high.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters].
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave this message to Solomon: '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CConcerning this Temple you are building, if you keep all my
        decrees and regulations and obey all my commands, I will fulfill through
        you the promise I made to your father, David. "
      comments: []
    - name: "13: The Temple\u2019s Interior"
      title: "The Temple\u2019s Interior"
      number: 13
      content: "I will live among the Israelites and will never abandon my people
        Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So Solomon finished building the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The entire inside, from floor to ceiling, was paneled with wood.
        He paneled the walls and ceilings with cedar, and he used planks of cypress
        for the floors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "He partitioned off an inner sanctuary\u2014the Most Holy Place\u2014at
        the far end of the Temple. It was 30 feet deep and was paneled with cedar
        from floor to ceiling. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The main room of the Temple, outside the Most Holy Place, was 60
        feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>40 cubits </b>[18.4 meters].
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Cedar paneling completely covered the stone walls throughout the
        Temple, and the paneling was decorated with carvings of gourds and open flowers.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He prepared the inner sanctuary at the far end of the Temple, where
        the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant would be placed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'This inner sanctuary was 30 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 30 feet
        high. He overlaid the inside with solid gold. He also overlaid the altar
        made of cedar.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:20 '
        content: Or <b>overlaid the altar with cedar. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Solomon overlaid the rest of the Temple\u2019s interior with
        solid gold, and he made gold chains to protect the entrance[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to the Most Holy Place. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:21 '
        content: Or <b>to draw curtains across. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is
          uncertain.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So he finished overlaying the entire Temple with gold, including
        the altar that belonged to the Most Holy Place.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'He made two cherubim of wild olive[[COMMENT(0)]] wood, each 15 feet[[COMMENT(1)]]
        tall, and placed them in the inner sanctuary. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:23a '
        content: Or <b>pine; </b>Hebrew reads <b>oil tree; </b>also in 6:31, 33.
      - number: '6:23b '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters]; also in 6:24, 26.
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'The wingspan of each of the cherubim was 15 feet, each wing being
        7-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters].
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The two cherubim were identical in shape and size; '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'each was 15 feet tall. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'He placed them side by side in the inner sanctuary of the Temple.
        Their outspread wings reached from wall to wall, while their inner wings
        touched at the center of the room. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'He overlaid the two cherubim with gold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'He decorated all the walls of the inner sanctuary and the main room
        with carvings of cherubim, palm trees, and open flowers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'He overlaid the floor in both rooms with gold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'For the entrance to the inner sanctuary, he made double doors of
        wild olive wood with five-sided doorposts.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:31 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'These double doors were decorated with carvings of cherubim, palm
        trees, and open flowers. The doors, including the decorations of cherubim
        and palm trees, were overlaid with gold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Then he made four-sided doorposts of wild olive wood for the entrance
        to the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'There were two folding doors of cypress wood, and each door was hinged
        to fold back upon itself. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "These doors were decorated with carvings of cherubim, palm trees,
        and open flowers\u2014all overlaid evenly with gold.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'The walls of the inner courtyard were built so that there was one
        layer of cedar beams between every three layers of finished stone.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "The foundation of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple was
        laid in midspring, in the month of Ziv,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the fourth year
        of Solomon\u2019s reign. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:37 '
        content: Hebrew <b>was laid in the month of Ziv. </b>This month of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of April and May.
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: The entire building was completed in every detail by midautumn, in
        the month of Bul,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the eleventh year of his reign. So
        it took seven years to build the Temple.
      comments:
      - number: '6:38 '
        content: Hebrew <b>by the month of Bul, which is the eighth month. </b>This
          month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months
          of October and November.
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Solomon Builds His Palace'
      title: Solomon Builds His Palace
      number: 1
      content: '  Solomon also built a palace for himself, and it took him thirteen
        years to complete the construction.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "One of Solomon\u2019s buildings was called the Palace of the Forest
        of Lebanon. It was 150 feet long, 75 feet wide, and 45 feet high.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        There were four rows of cedar pillars, and great cedar beams rested on the
        pillars. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[46 meters] <b>long, 50 cubits </b>[23
          meters] <b>wide, and 30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The hall had a cedar roof. Above the beams on the pillars were forty-five
        side rooms,[[COMMENT(0)]] arranged in three tiers of fifteen each. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:3 '
        content: Or <b>45 rafters, </b>or <b>45 beams, </b>or <b>45 pillars. </b>The
          architectural details in 7:2-6 can be interpreted in many different ways.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'On each end of the long hall were three rows of windows facing each
        other. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'All the doorways and doorposts[[COMMENT(0)]] had rectangular frames
        and were arranged in sets of three, facing each other.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:5 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>windows.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Solomon also built the Hall of Pillars, which was 75 feet long and
        45 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]] There was a porch in front, along with a canopy
        supported by pillars.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[23 meters] <b>long and 30 cubits </b>[13.8
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Solomon also built the throne room, known as the Hall of Justice,
        where he sat to hear legal matters. It was paneled with cedar from floor
        to ceiling.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:7 '
        content: As in Syriac version and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads <b>from floor
          to floor.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Solomon\u2019s living quarters surrounded a courtyard behind this
        hall, and they were constructed the same way. He also built similar living
        quarters for Pharaoh\u2019s daughter, whom he had married.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'From foundation to eaves, all these buildings were built from huge
        blocks of high-quality stone, cut with saws and trimmed to exact measure
        on all sides. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Some of the huge foundation stones were 15 feet long, and some were
        12 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] . . . <b>8 cubits </b>[3.7
          meters].
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The blocks of high-quality stone used in the walls were also cut
        to measure, and cedar beams were also used. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Furnishings for the Temple'
      title: Furnishings for the Temple
      number: 12
      content: "The walls of the great courtyard were built so that there was one
        layer of cedar beams between every three layers of finished stone, just like
        the walls of the inner courtyard of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple with its entry room.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'King Solomon then asked for a man named Huram[[COMMENT(0)]] to come
        from Tyre. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Hiram </b>(also in 7:40, 45); compare 2 Chr 2:13. This
          is not the same person mentioned in 5:1.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'He was half Israelite, since his mother was a widow from the tribe
        of Naphtali, and his father had been a craftsman in bronze from Tyre. Huram
        was extremely skillful and talented in any work in bronze, and he came to
        do all the metal work for King Solomon.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Huram cast two bronze pillars, each 27 feet tall and 18 feet in circumference.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>18 cubits </b>[8.3 meters] <b>tall and 12 cubits </b>[5.5
          meters] <b>in circumference.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'For the tops of the pillars he cast bronze capitals, each 7-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        tall. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters].
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Each capital was decorated with seven sets of latticework and interwoven
        chains. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He also encircled the latticework with two rows of pomegranates to
        decorate the capitals over the pillars. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The capitals on the columns inside the entry room were shaped like
        water lilies, and they were six feet[[COMMENT(0)]] tall. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>4 cubits </b>[1.8 meters]; also in 7:38.
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The capitals on the two pillars had 200 pomegranates in two rows
        around them, beside the rounded surface next to the latticework. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Huram set the pillars at the entrance of the Temple, one toward the
        south and one toward the north. He named the one on the south Jakin, and
        the one on the north Boaz.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:21 '
        content: "<b>Jakin </b>probably means \u201Che establishes\u201D; <b>Boaz
          </b>probably means \u201Cin him is strength.\u201D"
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The capitals on the pillars were shaped like water lilies. And so
        the work on the pillars was finished.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Then Huram cast a great round basin, 15 feet across from rim to rim,
        called the Sea. It was 7-1/2 feet deep and about 45 feet in circumference.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] <b>across. . . . 5 cubits </b>[2.3
          meters] <b>deep and 30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>in circumference.</b>
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'It was encircled just below its rim by two rows of decorative gourds.
        There were about six gourds per foot[[COMMENT(0)]] all the way around, and
        they were cast as part of the basin.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:24 '
        content: Or <b>20 gourds per meter; </b>Hebrew reads <b>10 per cubit.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The Sea was placed on a base of twelve bronze oxen,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        all facing outward. Three faced north, three faced west, three faced south,
        and three faced east, and the Sea rested on them. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>12 oxen; </b>compare 2 Kgs 16:17, which specifies <b>bronze
          oxen.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'The walls of the Sea were about three inches[[COMMENT(0)]] thick,
        and its rim flared out like a cup and resembled a water lily blossom. It
        could hold about 11,000 gallons[[COMMENT(1)]] of water.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:26a '
        content: Hebrew <b>a handbreadth </b>[8 centimeters].
      - number: '7:26b '
        content: Hebrew <b>2,000 baths </b>[42 kiloliters].
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Huram also made ten bronze water carts, each 6 feet long, 6 feet
        wide, and 4-1/2 feet tall.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>4 cubits </b>[1.8 meters] <b>long, 4 cubits wide, and
          3 cubits </b>[1.4 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They were constructed with side panels braced with crossbars. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Both the panels and the crossbars were decorated with carved lions,
        oxen, and cherubim. Above and below the lions and oxen were wreath decorations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Each of these carts had four bronze wheels and bronze axles. There
        were supporting posts for the bronze basins at the corners of the carts;
        these supports were decorated on each side with carvings of wreaths. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "The top of each cart had a rounded frame for the basin. It projected
        1-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] above the cart\u2019s top like a round pedestal,
        and its opening was 2-1/4 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] across; it was decorated on
        the outside with carvings of wreaths. The panels of the carts were square,
        not round. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:31a '
        content: Hebrew <b>a cubit </b>[46 centimeters].
      - number: '7:31b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1-1/2 cubits </b>[69 centimeters]; also in 7:32.
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Under the panels were four wheels that were connected to axles that
        had been cast as one unit with the cart. The wheels were 2-1/4 feet in diameter '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'and were similar to chariot wheels. The axles, spokes, rims, and
        hubs were all cast from molten bronze.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'There were handles at each of the four corners of the carts, and
        these, too, were cast as one unit with the cart. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Around the top of each cart was a rim nine inches wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        The corner supports and side panels were cast as one unit with the cart. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:35 '
        content: Hebrew <b>half a cubit wide </b>[23 centimeters].
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Carvings of cherubim, lions, and palm trees decorated the panels
        and corner supports wherever there was room, and there were wreaths all around. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'All ten water carts were the same size and were made alike, for each
        was cast from the same mold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Huram also made ten smaller bronze basins, one for each cart. Each
        basin was six feet across and could hold 220 gallons[[COMMENT(0)]] of water. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:38 '
        content: Hebrew <b>40 baths </b>[840 liters].
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'He set five water carts on the south side of the Temple and five
        on the north side. The great bronze basin called the Sea was placed near
        the southeast corner of the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'He also made the necessary washbasins, shovels, and bowls.So at last
        Huram completed everything King Solomon had assigned him to make for the
        Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'the two pillars;the two bowl-shaped capitals on top of the pillars;the
        two networks of interwoven chains that decorated the capitals;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'the 400 pomegranates that hung from the chains on the capitals (two
        rows of pomegranates for each of the chain networks that decorated the capitals
        on top of the pillars);  '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'the ten water carts holding the ten basins;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'the Sea and the twelve oxen under it;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'the ash buckets, the shovels, and the bowls.Huram made all these
        things of burnished bronze for the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        just as King Solomon had directed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'The king had them cast in clay molds in the Jordan Valley between
        Succoth and Zarethan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: 'Solomon did not weigh all these things because there were so many;
        the weight of the bronze could not be measured.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Solomon also made all the furnishings of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:the
        gold altar;the gold table for the Bread of the Presence;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "the lampstands of solid gold, five on the south and five on the north,
        in front of the Most Holy Place;the flower decorations, lamps, and tongs\u2014all
        of gold;  "
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: "the small bowls, lamp snuffers, bowls, ladles, and incense burners\u2014all
        of solid gold;the doors for the entrances to the Most Holy Place and the
        main room of the Temple, with their fronts overlaid with gold.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "So King Solomon finished all his work on the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then he brought all the gifts his father, David, had dedicated\u2014the silver,
        the gold, and the various articles\u2014and he stored them in the treasuries
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Ark Brought to the Temple'
      title: The Ark Brought to the Temple
      number: 1
      content: "  Solomon then summoned to Jerusalem the elders of Israel and all
        the heads of the tribes\u2014the leaders of the ancestral families of the
        Israelites. They were to bring the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Covenant to the Temple from its location in the City of David, also known
        as Zion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So all the men of Israel assembled before King Solomon at the annual
        Festival of Shelters, which is held in early autumn in the month of Ethanim.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at the festival in the month Ethanim, which is the seventh
          month. </b>The Festival of Shelters began on the fifteenth day of the seventh
          month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This day occurred in late September,
          October, or early November.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When all the elders of Israel arrived, the priests picked up the
        Ark. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The priests and Levites brought up the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        along with the special tent[[COMMENT(0)]] and all the sacred items that had
        been in it. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tent of Meeting; </b>i.e., the tent mentioned in 2
          Sam 6:17 and 1 Chr 16:1.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'There, before the Ark, King Solomon and the entire community of Israel
        sacrificed so many sheep, goats, and cattle that no one could keep count!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then the priests carried the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Covenant into the inner sanctuary of the Temple\u2014the Most Holy Place\u2014and
        placed it beneath the wings of the cherubim. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The cherubim spread their wings over the Ark, forming a canopy over
        the Ark and its carrying poles. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'These poles were so long that their ends could be seen from the Holy
        Place, which is in front of the Most Holy Place, but not from the outside.
        They are still there to this day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Nothing was in the Ark except the two stone tablets that Moses had
        placed in it at Mount Sinai,[[COMMENT(0)]] where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        made a covenant with the people of Israel when they left the land of Egypt.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'When the priests came out of the Holy Place, a thick cloud filled
        the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Solomon Praises the '
      title: 'Solomon Praises the '
      number: 11
      content: 'The priests could not continue their service because of the cloud,
        for the glorious presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then Solomon prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, you have
        said that you would live in a thick cloud of darkness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Now I have built a glorious Temple for you, a place where you can
        live forever![[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: Some Greek texts add the line <b>Is this not written in the Book
          of Jashar?</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Then the king turned around to the entire community of Israel standing
        before him and gave this blessing: '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        who has kept the promise he made to my father, David. For he told my father, "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u2018From the day I brought my people Israel out of Egypt, I have
        never chosen a city among any of the tribes of Israel as the place where
        a Temple should be built to honor my name. But I have chosen David to be
        king over my people Israel.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Solomon said, \u201CMy father, David, wanted to build this Temple
        to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u2018You wanted to
        build the Temple to honor my name. Your intention is good, "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "but you are not the one to do it. One of your own sons will build
        the Temple to honor me.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CAnd now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has fulfilled the promise
        he made, for I have become king in my father\u2019s place, and now I sit
        on the throne of Israel, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> promised.
        I have built this Temple to honor the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: "21: Solomon\u2019s Prayer of Dedication"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Prayer of Dedication"
      number: 21
      content: "And I have prepared a place there for the Ark, which contains the
        covenant that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made with our ancestors when
        he brought them out of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Then Solomon stood before the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in front of the entire community of Israel. He lifted his hands toward heaven, '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "and he prayed,\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel,
        there is no God like you in all of heaven above or on the earth below. You
        keep your covenant and show unfailing love to all who walk before you in
        wholehearted devotion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'You have kept your promise to your servant David, my father. You
        made that promise with your own mouth, and with your own hands you have fulfilled
        it today.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CAnd now, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, carry
        out the additional promise you made to your servant David, my father. For
        you said to him, \u2018If your descendants guard their behavior and faithfully
        follow me as you have done, one of them will always sit on the throne of
        Israel.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Now, O God of Israel, fulfill this promise to your servant David,
        my father.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CBut will God really live on earth? Why, even the highest heavens
        cannot contain you. How much less this Temple I have built! "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Nevertheless, listen to my prayer and my plea, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God. Hear the cry and the prayer that your servant is making to you today. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "May you watch over this Temple night and day, this place where you
        have said, \u2018My name will be there.\u2019 May you always hear the prayers
        I make toward this place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'May you hear the humble and earnest requests from me and your people
        Israel when we pray toward this place. Yes, hear us from heaven where you
        live, and when you hear, forgive.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CIf someone wrongs another person and is required to take an
        oath of innocence in front of your altar in this Temple, "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "then hear from heaven and judge between your servants\u2014the accuser
        and the accused. Punish the guilty as they deserve. Acquit the innocent because
        of their innocence.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CIf your people Israel are defeated by their enemies because
        they have sinned against you, and if they turn to you and acknowledge your
        name and pray to you here in this Temple, "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sin of your people Israel and
        return them to this land you gave their ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201CIf the skies are shut up and there is no rain because your
        people have sinned against you, and if they pray toward this Temple and acknowledge
        your name and turn from their sins because you have punished them, "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sins of your servants, your
        people Israel. Teach them to follow the right path, and send rain on your
        land that you have given to your people as their special possession.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "\u201CIf there is a famine in the land or a plague or crop disease
        or attacks of locusts or caterpillars, or if your people\u2019s enemies are
        in the land besieging their towns\u2014whatever disaster or disease there
        is\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'and if your people Israel pray about their troubles, raising their
        hands toward this Temple, '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'then hear from heaven where you live, and forgive. Give your people
        what their actions deserve, for you alone know each human heart. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'Then they will fear you as long as they live in the land you gave
        to our ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "\u201CIn the future, foreigners who do not belong to your people
        Israel will hear of you. They will come from distant lands because of your
        name, "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'for they will hear of your great name and your strong hand and your
        powerful arm. And when they pray toward this Temple, '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'then hear from heaven where you live, and grant what they ask of
        you. In this way, all the people of the earth will come to know and fear
        you, just as your own people Israel do. They, too, will know that this Temple
        I have built honors your name.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "\u201CIf your people go out where you send them to fight their enemies,
        and if they pray to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by turning toward this
        city you have chosen and toward this Temple I have built to honor your name, "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'then hear their prayers from heaven and uphold their cause.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "\u201CIf they sin against you\u2014and who has never sinned?\u2014you
        might become angry with them and let their enemies conquer them and take
        them captive to their land far away or near. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "But in that land of exile, they might turn to you in repentance and
        pray, \u2018We have sinned, done evil, and acted wickedly.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "If they turn to you with their whole heart and soul in the land of
        their enemies and pray toward the land you gave to their ancestors\u2014toward
        this city you have chosen, and toward this Temple I have built to honor your
        name\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: 'then hear their prayers and their petition from heaven where you
        live, and uphold their cause. '
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'Forgive your people who have sinned against you. Forgive all the
        offenses they have committed against you. Make their captors merciful to
        them, '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "for they are your people\u2014your special possession\u2014whom you
        brought out of the iron-smelting furnace of Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "\u201CMay your eyes be open to my requests and to the requests of
        your people Israel. May you hear and answer them whenever they cry out to
        you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '53: The Dedication of the Temple'
      title: The Dedication of the Temple
      number: 53
      content: "For when you brought our ancestors out of Egypt, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        you told your servant Moses that you had set Israel apart from all the nations
        of the earth to be your own special possession.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: 'When Solomon finished making these prayers and petitions to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        he stood up in front of the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, where
        he had been kneeling with his hands raised toward heaven. '
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: 'He stood and in a loud voice blessed the entire congregation of Israel:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: "\u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who has given rest to
        his people Israel, just as he promised. Not one word has failed of all the
        wonderful promises he gave through his servant Moses. "
      comments: []
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: 'May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God be with us as he was
        with our ancestors; may he never leave us or abandon us. '
      comments: []
    - name: '58: '
      title: 
      number: 58
      content: 'May he give us the desire to do his will in everything and to obey
        all the commands, decrees, and regulations that he gave our ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: "And may these words that I have prayed in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        be before him constantly, day and night, so that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God may give justice to me and to his people Israel, according to each
        day\u2019s needs. "
      comments: []
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: 'Then people all over the earth will know that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        alone is God and there is no other. '
      comments: []
    - name: '61: '
      title: 
      number: 61
      content: "And may you be completely faithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God. May you always obey his decrees and commands, just as you are doing
        today.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '62: '
      title: 
      number: 62
      content: 'Then the king and all Israel with him offered sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '63: '
      title: 
      number: 63
      content: 'Solomon offered to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> a peace offering
        of 22,000 cattle and 120,000 sheep and goats. And so the king and all the
        people of Israel dedicated the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '64: '
      title: 
      number: 64
      content: "That same day the king consecrated the central area of the courtyard
        in front of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. He offered burnt
        offerings, grain offerings, and the fat of peace offerings there, because
        the bronze altar in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence was too
        small to hold all the burnt offerings, grain offerings, and the fat of the
        peace offerings.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '65: '
      title: 
      number: 65
      content: "Then Solomon and all Israel celebrated the Festival of Shelters[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God. A large congregation
        had gathered from as far away as Lebo-hamath in the north and the Brook of
        Egypt in the south. The celebration went on for fourteen days in all\u2014seven
        days for the dedication of the altar and seven days for the Festival of Shelters.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:65a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the festival; </b>see note on 8:2.
      - number: '8:65b '
        content: Hebrew <b>seven days and seven days, fourteen days; </b>compare
          parallel text at 2 Chr 7:8-10.
    - name: '66: '
      title: 
      number: 66
      content: After the festival was over,[[COMMENT(0)]] Solomon sent the people
        home. They blessed the king and went to their homes joyful and glad because
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had been good to his servant David and to
        his people Israel.
      comments:
      - number: '8:66 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the eighth day, </b>probably referring to the day following
          the seven-day Festival of Shelters; compare parallel text at 2 Chr 7:9-10.
  - verses:
    - name: "1: The \u2019s Response to Solomon"
      title: "The \u2019s Response to Solomon"
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  So Solomon finished building the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, as well as the royal palace. He completed
        everything he had planned to do. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to Solomon a second
        time, as he had done before at Gibeon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to him,\u201CI have heard your
        prayer and your petition. I have set this Temple apart to be holy\u2014this
        place you have built where my name will be honored forever. I will always
        watch over it, for it is dear to my heart.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CAs for you, if you will follow me with integrity and godliness,
        as David your father did, obeying all my commands, decrees, and regulations, "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "then I will establish the throne of your dynasty over Israel forever.
        For I made this promise to your father, David: \u2018One of your descendants
        will always sit on the throne of Israel.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CBut if you or your descendants abandon me and disobey the commands
        and decrees I have given you, and if you serve and worship other gods, "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'then I will uproot Israel from this land that I have given them.
        I will reject this Temple that I have made holy to honor my name. I will
        make Israel an object of mockery and ridicule among the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "And though this Temple is impressive now, all who pass by will be
        appalled and will gasp in horror. They will ask, \u2018Why did the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        do such terrible things to this land and to this Temple?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: "9: Solomon\u2019s Agreement with Hiram"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Agreement with Hiram"
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CAnd the answer will be, \u2018Because his people abandoned
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God, who brought their ancestors out
        of Egypt, and they worshiped other gods instead and bowed down to them. That
        is why the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has brought all these disasters on
        them.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "It took Solomon twenty years to build the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and his own royal palace. At the end of that time, "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'he gave twenty towns in the land of Galilee to King Hiram of Tyre.
        (Hiram had previously provided all the cedar and cypress timber and gold
        that Solomon had requested.) '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But when Hiram came from Tyre to see the towns Solomon had given
        him, he was not at all pleased with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CWhat kind of towns are these, my brother?\u201D he asked. So
        Hiram called that area Cabul (which means \u201Cworthless\u201D), as it is
        still known today. "
      comments: []
    - name: "14: Solomon\u2019s Many Achievements"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Many Achievements"
      number: 14
      content: 'Nevertheless, Hiram paid[[COMMENT(0)]] Solomon 9,000 pounds[[COMMENT(1)]]
        of gold.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:14a '
        content: Or <b>For Hiram had paid.</b>
      - number: '9:14b '
        content: Hebrew <b>120 talents </b>[4,000 kilograms].
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "This is the account of the forced labor that King Solomon conscripted
        to build the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple, the royal palace,
        the supporting terraces,[[COMMENT(0)]] the wall of Jerusalem, and the cities
        of Hazor, Megiddo, and Gezer. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the millo; </b>also in 9:24. The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: '(Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, had attacked and captured Gezer, killing
        the Canaanite population and burning it down. He gave the city to his daughter
        as a wedding gift when she married Solomon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'So Solomon rebuilt the city of Gezer.) He also built up the towns
        of Lower Beth-horon, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Baalath, and Tamar[[COMMENT(0)]] in the wilderness within his land. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:18 '
        content: An alternate reading in the Masoretic Text reads <b>Tadmor.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'He built towns as supply centers and constructed towns where his
        chariots and horses[[COMMENT(0)]] could be stationed. He built everything
        he desired in Jerusalem and Lebanon and throughout his entire realm.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:19 '
        content: Or <b>and charioteers.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'There were still some people living in the land who were not Israelites,
        including Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: These were descendants of the nations whom the people of Israel had
        not completely destroyed.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> So Solomon conscripted
        them as slaves, and they serve as forced laborers to this day. </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '9:21 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But Solomon did not conscript any of the Israelites for forced labor.
        Instead, he assigned them to serve as fighting men, government officials,
        officers and captains in his army, commanders of his chariots, and charioteers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Solomon appointed 550 of them to supervise the people working on
        his various projects.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Solomon moved his wife, Pharaoh\u2019s daughter, from the City of
        David to the new palace he had built for her. Then he constructed the supporting
        terraces.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Three times each year Solomon presented burnt offerings and peace
        offerings on the altar he had built for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        He also burned incense to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. And so he finished
        the work of building the Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'King Solomon also built a fleet of ships at Ezion-geber, a port near
        Elath[[COMMENT(0)]] in the land of Edom, along the shore of the Red Sea.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:26a '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 2 Kgs 14:22; 16:6); Hebrew reads <b>Eloth,
          </b>a variant spelling of Elath.
      - number: '9:26b '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Hiram sent experienced crews of sailors to sail the ships with Solomon\u2019s
        men. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: They sailed to Ophir and brought back to Solomon some sixteen tons[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of gold.
      comments:
      - number: '9:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>420 talents </b>[14 metric tons].
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Visit of the Queen of Sheba'
      title: Visit of the Queen of Sheba
      number: 1
      content: "  When the queen of Sheba heard of Solomon\u2019s fame, which brought
        honor to the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>The
        meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.</smallcaps> she came to test him with
        hard questions. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: Or <b>which was due to the name of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.
          </b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'She arrived in Jerusalem with a large group of attendants and a great
        caravan of camels loaded with spices, large quantities of gold, and precious
        jewels. When she met with Solomon, she talked with him about everything she
        had on her mind. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Solomon had answers for all her questions; nothing was too hard for
        the king to explain to her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When the queen of Sheba realized how very wise Solomon was, and when
        she saw the palace he had built, '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'she was overwhelmed. She was also amazed at the food on his tables,
        the organization of his officials and their splendid clothing, the cup-bearers,
        and the burnt offerings Solomon made at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "She exclaimed to the king, \u201CEverything I heard in my country
        about your achievements[[COMMENT(0)]] and wisdom is true! "
      comments:
      - number: '10:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>your words.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "I didn\u2019t believe what was said until I arrived here and saw
        it with my own eyes. In fact, I had not heard the half of it! Your wisdom
        and prosperity are far beyond what I was told. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'How happy your people[[COMMENT(0)]] must be! What a privilege for
        your officials to stand here day after day, listening to your wisdom! '
      comments:
      - number: '10:8 '
        content: Greek and Syriac versions and Latin Vulgate read <b>your wives.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, who delights in
        you and has placed you on the throne of Israel. Because of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        eternal love for Israel, he has made you king so you can rule with justice
        and righteousness.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then she gave the king a gift of 9,000 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of gold,
        great quantities of spices, and precious jewels. Never again were so many
        spices brought in as those the queen of Sheba gave to King Solomon.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>120 talents </b>[4,000 kilograms].
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "(In addition, Hiram\u2019s ships brought gold from Ophir, and they
        also brought rich cargoes of red sandalwood[[COMMENT(0)]] and precious jewels. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>almug wood; </b>also in 10:12.
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The king used the sandalwood to make railings for the Temple of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and the royal palace, and to construct lyres
        and harps for the musicians. Never before or since has there been such a
        supply of sandalwood.)  '
      comments: []
    - name: "13: Solomon\u2019s Wealth and Splendor"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Wealth and Splendor"
      number: 13
      content: 'King Solomon gave the queen of Sheba whatever she asked for, besides
        all the customary gifts he had so generously given. Then she and all her
        attendants returned to their own land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Each year Solomon received about 25 tons[[COMMENT(0)]] of gold. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>666 talents </b>[23 metric tons].
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'This did not include the additional revenue he received from merchants
        and traders, all the kings of Arabia, and the governors of the land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'King Solomon made 200 large shields of hammered gold, each weighing
        more than fifteen pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 [shekels] of gold </b>[6.8 kilograms].
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'He also made 300 smaller shields of hammered gold, each weighing
        nearly four pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]] The king placed these shields in the Palace
        of the Forest of Lebanon.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>3 minas </b>[1.8 kilograms].
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then the king made a huge throne, decorated with ivory and overlaid
        with fine gold. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The throne had six steps and a rounded back. There were armrests
        on both sides of the seat, and the figure of a lion stood on each side of
        the throne. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'There were also twelve other lions, one standing on each end of the
        six steps. No other throne in all the world could be compared with it!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "All of King Solomon\u2019s drinking cups were solid gold, as were
        all the utensils in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon. They were not made
        of silver, for silver was considered worthless in Solomon\u2019s day!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The king had a fleet of trading ships of Tarshish that sailed with
        Hiram\u2019s fleet. Once every three years the ships returned, loaded with
        gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:22 '
        content: Or <b>and baboons.</b>
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'So King Solomon became richer and wiser than any other king on earth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'People from every nation came to consult him and to hear the wisdom
        God had given him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Year after year everyone who visited brought him gifts of silver
        and gold, clothing, weapons, spices, horses, and mules.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Solomon built up a huge force of chariots and horses.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        He had 1,400 chariots and 12,000 horses. He stationed some of them in the
        chariot cities and some near him in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:26 '
        content: Or <b>charioteers; </b>also in 10:26b.
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'The king made silver as plentiful in Jerusalem as stone. And valuable
        cedar timber was as common as the sycamore-fig trees that grow in the foothills
        of Judah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Solomon\u2019s horses were imported from Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        from Cilicia[[COMMENT(1)]]; the king\u2019s traders acquired them from Cilicia
        at the standard price. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:28a '
        content: Possibly <b>Muzur, </b>a district near Cilicia; also in 10:29.
      - number: '10:28b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Kue, </b>probably another name for Cilicia.
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: At that time chariots from Egypt could be purchased for 600 pieces
        of silver,[[COMMENT(0)]] and horses for 150 pieces of silver.[[COMMENT(1)]]
        They were then exported to the kings of the Hittites and the kings of Aram.
      comments:
      - number: '10:29a '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 [shekels] of silver, </b>about 15 pounds or 6.8 kilograms
          in weight.
      - number: '10:29b '
        content: Hebrew <b>150 [shekels], </b>about 3.8 pounds or 1.7 kilograms in
          weight.
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Solomon\u2019s Many Wives"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Many Wives"
      number: 1
      content: "  Now King Solomon loved many foreign women. Besides Pharaoh\u2019s
        daughter, he married women from Moab, Ammon, Edom, Sidon, and from among
        the Hittites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had clearly instructed the people
        of Israel, \u201CYou must not marry them, because they will turn your hearts
        to their gods.\u201D Yet Solomon insisted on loving them anyway. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He had 700 wives of royal birth and 300 concubines. And in fact,
        they did turn his heart away from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "In Solomon\u2019s old age, they turned his heart to worship other
        gods instead of being completely faithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God, as his father, David, had been. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Solomon worshiped Ashtoreth, the goddess of the Sidonians, and Molech,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the detestable god of the Ammonites. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Milcom, </b>a variant spelling of Molech; also in 11:33.
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "In this way, Solomon did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight; he refused to follow the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> completely, as
        his father, David, had done.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'On the Mount of Olives, east of Jerusalem,[[COMMENT(0)]] he even
        built a pagan shrine for Chemosh, the detestable god of Moab, and another
        for Molech, the detestable god of the Ammonites. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the mountain east of Jerusalem.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Solomon built such shrines for all his foreign wives to use for burning
        incense and sacrificing to their gods.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was very angry with Solomon, for
        his heart had turned away from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of
        Israel, who had appeared to him twice. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "He had warned Solomon specifically about worshiping other gods, but
        Solomon did not listen to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "So now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to him, \u201CSince you
        have not kept my covenant and have disobeyed my decrees, I will surely tear
        the kingdom away from you and give it to one of your servants. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But for the sake of your father, David, I will not do this while
        you are still alive. I will take the kingdom away from your son. '
      comments: []
    - name: "13: Solomon\u2019s Adversaries"
      title: "Solomon\u2019s Adversaries"
      number: 13
      content: "And even so, I will not take away the entire kingdom; I will let
        him be king of one tribe, for the sake of my servant David and for the sake
        of Jerusalem, my chosen city.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> raised up Hadad the Edomite,
        a member of Edom\u2019s royal family, to be Solomon\u2019s adversary. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Years before, David had defeated Edom. Joab, his army commander,
        had stayed to bury some of the Israelite soldiers who had died in battle.
        While there, they killed every male in Edom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Joab and the army of Israel had stayed there for six months, killing
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But Hadad and a few of his father\u2019s royal officials escaped
        and headed for Egypt. (Hadad was just a boy at the time.) "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'They set out from Midian and went to Paran, where others joined them.
        Then they traveled to Egypt and went to Pharaoh, who gave them a home, food,
        and some land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Pharaoh grew very fond of Hadad, and he gave him his wife\u2019s
        sister in marriage\u2014the sister of Queen Tahpenes. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "She bore him a son named Genubath. Tahpenes raised him[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in Pharaoh\u2019s palace among Pharaoh\u2019s own sons.  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:20 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>weaned him.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "When the news reached Hadad in Egypt that David and his commander
        Joab were both dead, he said to Pharaoh, \u201CLet me return to my own country.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CWhy?\u201D Pharaoh asked him. \u201CWhat do you lack here that
        makes you want to go home?\u201D\u201CNothing,\u201D he replied. \u201CBut
        even so, please let me return home.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "God also raised up Rezon son of Eliada as Solomon\u2019s adversary.
        Rezon had fled from his master, King Hadadezer of Zobah, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'and had become the leader of a gang of rebels. After David conquered
        Hadadezer, Rezon and his men fled to Damascus, where he became king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: Jeroboam Rebels against Solomon'
      title: Jeroboam Rebels against Solomon
      number: 25
      content: "Rezon was Israel\u2019s bitter adversary for the rest of Solomon\u2019s
        reign, and he made trouble, just as Hadad did. Rezon hated Israel intensely
        and continued to reign in Aram.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Another rebel leader was Jeroboam son of Nebat, one of Solomon\u2019s
        own officials. He came from the town of Zeredah in Ephraim, and his mother
        was Zeruah, a widow.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'This is the story behind his rebellion. Solomon was rebuilding the
        supporting terraces[[COMMENT(0)]] and repairing the walls of the city of
        his father, David. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the millo. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Jeroboam was a very capable young man, and when Solomon saw how industrious
        he was, he put him in charge of the labor force from the tribes of Ephraim
        and Manasseh, the descendants of Joseph.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'One day as Jeroboam was leaving Jerusalem, the prophet Ahijah from
        Shiloh met him along the way. Ahijah was wearing a new cloak. The two of
        them were alone in a field, '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'and Ahijah took hold of the new cloak he was wearing and tore it
        into twelve pieces. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then he said to Jeroboam, \u201CTake ten of these pieces, for this
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, says: \u2018I
        am about to tear the kingdom from the hand of Solomon, and I will give ten
        of the tribes to you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'But I will leave him one tribe for the sake of my servant David and
        for the sake of Jerusalem, which I have chosen out of all the tribes of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'For Solomon has[[COMMENT(0)]] abandoned me and worshiped Ashtoreth,
        the goddess of the Sidonians; Chemosh, the god of Moab; and Molech, the god
        of the Ammonites. He has not followed my ways and done what is pleasing in
        my sight. He has not obeyed my decrees and regulations as David his father
        did.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:33 '
        content: As in Greek, Syriac, and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads <b>For they
          have.</b>
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201C\u2018But I will not take the entire kingdom from Solomon at
        this time. For the sake of my servant David, the one whom I chose and who
        obeyed my commands and decrees, I will keep Solomon as leader for the rest
        of his life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'But I will take the kingdom away from his son and give ten of the
        tribes to you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'His son will have one tribe so that the descendants of David my servant
        will continue to reign, shining like a lamp in Jerusalem, the city I have
        chosen to be the place for my name. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'And I will place you on the throne of Israel, and you will rule over
        all that your heart desires. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'If you listen to what I tell you and follow my ways and do whatever
        I consider to be right, and if you obey my decrees and commands, as my servant
        David did, then I will always be with you. I will establish an enduring dynasty
        for you as I did for David, and I will give Israel to you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Because of Solomon\u2019s sin I will punish the descendants of David\u2014though
        not forever.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: "40: Summary of Solomon\u2019s Reign"
      title: "Summary of Solomon\u2019s Reign"
      number: 40
      content: 'Solomon tried to kill Jeroboam, but he fled to King Shishak of Egypt
        and stayed there until Solomon died.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "The rest of the events in Solomon\u2019s reign, including all his
        deeds and his wisdom, are recorded in The Book of the Acts of Solomon.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'Solomon ruled in Jerusalem over all Israel for forty years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: When he died, he was buried in the City of David, named for his father.
        Then his son Rehoboam became the next king.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Northern Tribes Revolt'
      title: The Northern Tribes Revolt
      number: 1
      content: '  Rehoboam went to Shechem, where all Israel had gathered to make
        him king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When Jeroboam son of Nebat heard of this, he returned from Egypt,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for he had fled to Egypt to escape from King Solomon. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:2 '
        content: As in Greek version and Latin Vulgate (see also 2 Chr 10:2); Hebrew
          reads <b>he lived in Egypt.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The leaders of Israel summoned him, and Jeroboam and the whole assembly
        of Israel went to speak with Rehoboam. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CYour father was a hard master,\u201D they said. \u201CLighten
        the harsh labor demands and heavy taxes that your father imposed on us. Then
        we will be your loyal subjects.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Rehoboam replied, \u201CGive me three days to think this over. Then
        come back for my answer.\u201D So the people went away.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then King Rehoboam discussed the matter with the older men who had
        counseled his father, Solomon. \u201CWhat is your advice?\u201D he asked.
        \u201CHow should I answer these people?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The older counselors replied, \u201CIf you are willing to be a servant
        to these people today and give them a favorable answer, they will always
        be your loyal subjects.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'But Rehoboam rejected the advice of the older men and instead asked
        the opinion of the young men who had grown up with him and were now his advisers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWhat is your advice?\u201D he asked them. \u201CHow should
        I answer these people who want me to lighten the burdens imposed by my father?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The young men replied, \u201CThis is what you should tell those complainers
        who want a lighter burden: \u2018My little finger is thicker than my father\u2019s
        waist! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Yes, my father laid heavy burdens on you, but I\u2019m going to make
        them even heavier! My father beat you with whips, but I will beat you with
        scorpions!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Three days later Jeroboam and all the people returned to hear Rehoboam\u2019s
        decision, just as the king had ordered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But Rehoboam spoke harshly to the people, for he rejected the advice
        of the older counselors '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "and followed the counsel of his younger advisers. He told the people,
        \u201CMy father laid heavy burdens on you, but I\u2019m going to make them
        even heavier! My father beat you with whips, but I will beat you with scorpions!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "So the king paid no attention to the people. This turn of events
        was the will of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for it fulfilled the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        message to Jeroboam son of Nebat through the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When all Israel realized that the king had refused to listen to them,
        they responded,\u201CDown with the dynasty of David!We have no interest in
        the son of Jesse.Back to your homes, O Israel!Look out for your own house,
        O David!\u201DSo the people of Israel returned home. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'But Rehoboam continued to rule over the Israelites who lived in the
        towns of Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'King Rehoboam sent Adoniram,[[COMMENT(0)]] who was in charge of forced
        labor, to restore order, but the people of Israel stoned him to death. When
        this news reached King Rehoboam, he quickly jumped into his chariot and fled
        to Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:18 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts and Syriac version (see also 4:6; 5:14);
          Hebrew reads <b>Adoram.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'And to this day the northern tribes of Israel have refused to be
        ruled by a descendant of David.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "20: Shemaiah\u2019s Prophecy"
      title: "Shemaiah\u2019s Prophecy"
      number: 20
      content: "When the people of Israel learned of Jeroboam\u2019s return from
        Egypt, they called an assembly and made him king over all Israel. So only
        the tribe of Judah remained loyal to the family of David.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "When Rehoboam arrived at Jerusalem, he mobilized the men of Judah
        and the tribe of Benjamin\u2014180,000 select troops\u2014to fight against
        the men of Israel and to restore the kingdom to himself.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But God said to Shemaiah, the man of God, '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CSay to Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, and to all the
        people of Judah and Benjamin, and to the rest of the people, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: Jeroboam Makes Gold Calves'
      title: Jeroboam Makes Gold Calves
      number: 24
      content: "\u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Do not fight
        against your relatives, the Israelites. Go back home, for what has happened
        is my doing!\u2019\u201D So they obeyed the message of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and went home, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Jeroboam then built up the city of Shechem in the hill country of
        Ephraim, and it became his capital. Later he went and built up the town of
        Peniel.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Penuel, </b>a variant spelling of Peniel.
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Jeroboam thought to himself, \u201CUnless I am careful, the kingdom
        will return to the dynasty of David. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "When these people go to Jerusalem to offer sacrifices at the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, they will again give their allegiance
        to King Rehoboam of Judah. They will kill me and make him their king instead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "So on the advice of his counselors, the king made two gold calves.
        He said to the people,[[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CIt is too much trouble for you
        to worship in Jerusalem. Look, Israel, these are the gods who brought you
        out of Egypt!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to them.</b>
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "He placed these calf idols in Bethel and in Dan\u2014at either end
        of his kingdom. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'But this became a great sin, for the people worshiped the idols,
        traveling as far north as Dan to worship the one there.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Jeroboam also erected buildings at the pagan shrines and ordained
        priests from the common people\u2014those who were not from the priestly
        tribe of Levi. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'And Jeroboam instituted a religious festival in Bethel, held on the
        fifteenth day of the eighth month,[[COMMENT(0)]] in imitation of the annual
        Festival of Shelters in Judah. There at Bethel he himself offered sacrifices
        to the calves he had made, and he appointed priests for the pagan shrines
        he had made. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:32 '
        content: This day of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in late October
          or early November, exactly one month after the annual Festival of Shelters
          in Judah (see Lev 23:34).
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: So on the fifteenth day of the eighth month, a day that he himself
        had designated, Jeroboam offered sacrifices on the altar at Bethel. He instituted
        a religious festival for Israel, and he went up to the altar to burn incense.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Prophet Denounces Jeroboam'
      title: A Prophet Denounces Jeroboam
      number: 1
      content: "  At the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command, a man of God
        from Judah went to Bethel, arriving there just as Jeroboam was approaching
        the altar to burn incense. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then at the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command, he shouted,
        \u201CO altar, altar! This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        A child named Josiah will be born into the dynasty of David. On you he will
        sacrifice the priests from the pagan shrines who come here to burn incense,
        and human bones will be burned on you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "That same day the man of God gave a sign to prove his message. He
        said, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has promised to give this sign:
        This altar will split apart, and its ashes will be poured out on the ground.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "When King Jeroboam heard the man of God speaking against the altar
        at Bethel, he pointed at him and shouted, \u201CSeize that man!\u201D But
        instantly the king\u2019s hand became paralyzed in that position, and he
        couldn\u2019t pull it back. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'At the same time a wide crack appeared in the altar, and the ashes
        poured out, just as the man of God had predicted in his message from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The king cried out to the man of God, \u201CPlease ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God to restore my hand again!\u201D So the man of God prayed to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the king\u2019s hand was restored and he
        could move it again.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then the king said to the man of God, \u201CCome to the palace with
        me and have something to eat, and I will give you a gift.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But the man of God said to the king, \u201CEven if you gave me half
        of everything you own, I would not go with you. I would not eat or drink
        anything in this place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave me this command: \u2018You
        must not eat or drink anything while you are there, and do not return to
        Judah by the same way you came.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So he left Bethel and went home another way.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'As it happened, there was an old prophet living in Bethel, and his
        sons[[COMMENT(0)]] came home and told him what the man of God had done in
        Bethel that day. They also told their father what the man had said to the
        king. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:11 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>son.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "The old prophet asked them, \u201CWhich way did he go?\u201D So they
        showed their father[[COMMENT(0)]] which road the man of God had taken. "
      comments:
      - number: '13:12 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>They had seen.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CQuick, saddle the donkey,\u201D the old man said. So they saddled
        the donkey for him, and he mounted it.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then he rode after the man of God and found him sitting under a great
        tree. The old prophet asked him, \u201CAre you the man of God who came from
        Judah?\u201D\u201CYes, I am,\u201D he replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then he said to the man of God, \u201CCome home with me and eat some
        food.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CNo, I cannot,\u201D he replied. \u201CI am not allowed to eat
        or drink anything here in this place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave me this command: \u2018You
        must not eat or drink anything while you are there, and do not return to
        Judah by the same way you came.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But the old prophet answered, \u201CI am a prophet, too, just as
        you are. And an angel gave me this command from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        \u2018Bring him home with you so he can have something to eat and drink.\u2019\u201D
        But the old man was lying to him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "So they went back together, and the man of God ate and drank at the
        prophet\u2019s home.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then while they were sitting at the table, a command from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        came to the old prophet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "He cried out to the man of God from Judah, \u201CThis is what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: You have defied the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and have disobeyed the command the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God gave
        you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "You came back to this place and ate and drank where he told you not
        to eat or drink. Because of this, your body will not be buried in the grave
        of your ancestors.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'After the man of God had finished eating and drinking, the old prophet
        saddled his own donkey for him, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'and the man of God started off again. But as he was traveling along,
        a lion came out and killed him. His body lay there on the road, with the
        donkey and the lion standing beside it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'People who passed by saw the body lying in the road and the lion
        standing beside it, and they went and reported it in Bethel, where the old
        prophet lived.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "When the prophet heard the report, he said, \u201CIt is the man of
        God who disobeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has fulfilled his word by causing the lion to attack and kill him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then the prophet said to his sons, \u201CSaddle a donkey for me.\u201D
        So they saddled a donkey, "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'and he went out and found the body lying in the road. The donkey
        and lion were still standing there beside it, for the lion had not eaten
        the body nor attacked the donkey. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So the prophet laid the body of the man of God on the donkey and
        took it back to the town to mourn over him and bury him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "He laid the body in his own grave, crying out in grief, \u201COh,
        my brother!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Afterward the prophet said to his sons, \u201CWhen I die, bury me
        in the grave where the man of God is buried. Lay my bones beside his bones. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "For the message the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him to proclaim
        against the altar in Bethel and against the pagan shrines in the towns of
        Samaria will certainly come true.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'But even after this, Jeroboam did not turn from his evil ways. He
        continued to choose priests from the common people. He appointed anyone who
        wanted to become a priest for the pagan shrines. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "This became a great sin and resulted in the utter destruction of
        Jeroboam\u2019s dynasty from the face of the earth."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Ahijah\u2019s Prophecy against Jeroboam"
      title: "Ahijah\u2019s Prophecy against Jeroboam"
      number: 1
      content: "  At that time Jeroboam\u2019s son Abijah became very sick. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So Jeroboam told his wife, \u201CDisguise yourself so that no one
        will recognize you as my wife. Then go to the prophet Ahijah at Shiloh\u2014the
        man who told me I would become king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Take him a gift of ten loaves of bread, some cakes, and a jar of
        honey, and ask him what will happen to the boy.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So Jeroboam\u2019s wife went to Ahijah\u2019s home at Shiloh. He
        was an old man now and could no longer see. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told Ahijah, \u201CJeroboam\u2019s
        wife will come here, pretending to be someone else. She will ask you about
        her son, for he is very sick. Give her the answer I give you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So when Ahijah heard her footsteps at the door, he called out, \u201CCome
        in, wife of Jeroboam! Why are you pretending to be someone else?\u201D Then
        he told her, \u201CI have bad news for you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Give your husband, Jeroboam, this message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel: \u2018I promoted you from the ranks of the common people
        and made you ruler over my people Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'I ripped the kingdom away from the family of David and gave it to
        you. But you have not been like my servant David, who obeyed my commands
        and followed me with all his heart and always did whatever I wanted. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'You have done more evil than all who lived before you. You have made
        other gods for yourself and have made me furious with your gold calves. And
        since you have turned your back on me, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'I will bring disaster on your dynasty and will destroy every one
        of your male descendants, slave and free alike, anywhere in Israel. I will
        burn up your royal dynasty as one burns up trash until it is all gone. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The members of Jeroboam\u2019s family who die in the city will be
        eaten by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by vultures.
        I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then Ahijah said to Jeroboam\u2019s wife, \u201CGo on home, and when
        you enter the city, the child will die. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'All Israel will mourn for him and bury him. He is the only member
        of your family who will have a proper burial, for this child is the only
        good thing that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, sees
        in the entire family of Jeroboam.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CIn addition, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will raise up
        a king over Israel who will destroy the family of Jeroboam. This will happen
        today, even now! "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will shake Israel like a reed
        whipped about in a stream. He will uproot the people of Israel from this
        good land that he gave their ancestors and will scatter them beyond the Euphrates
        River,[[COMMENT(0)]] for they have angered the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with the Asherah poles they have set up for worship. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "He will abandon Israel because Jeroboam sinned and made Israel sin
        along with him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So Jeroboam\u2019s wife returned to Tirzah, and the child died just
        as she walked through the door of her home. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'And all Israel buried him and mourned for him, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had promised through the prophet Ahijah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "The rest of the events in Jeroboam\u2019s reign, including all his
        wars and how he ruled, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings
        of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: Rehoboam Rules in Judah'
      title: Rehoboam Rules in Judah
      number: 20
      content: 'Jeroboam reigned in Israel twenty-two years. When Jeroboam died,
        his son Nadab became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Meanwhile, Rehoboam son of Solomon was king in Judah. He was forty-one
        years old when he became king, and he reigned seventeen years in Jerusalem,
        the city the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had chosen from among all the tribes
        of Israel as the place to honor his name. Rehoboam\u2019s mother was Naamah,
        an Ammonite woman.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "During Rehoboam\u2019s reign, the people of Judah did what was evil
        in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight, provoking his anger with
        their sin, for it was even worse than that of their ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'For they also built for themselves pagan shrines and set up sacred
        pillars and Asherah poles on every high hill and under every green tree. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'There were even male and female shrine prostitutes throughout the
        land. The people imitated the detestable practices of the pagan nations the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "In the fifth year of King Rehoboam\u2019s reign, King Shishak of
        Egypt came up and attacked Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "He ransacked the treasuries of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and the royal palace; he stole everything, including all the gold
        shields Solomon had made. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'King Rehoboam later replaced them with bronze shields as substitutes,
        and he entrusted them to the care of the commanders of the guard who protected
        the entrance to the royal palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Whenever the king went to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the guards would also take the shields and then return them to the guardroom.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The rest of the events in Rehoboam\u2019s reign and everything he
        did are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'There was constant war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: When Rehoboam died, he was buried among his ancestors in the City
        of David. His mother was Naamah, an Ammonite woman. Then his son Abijam[[COMMENT(0)]]
        became the next king.
      comments:
      - number: '14:31 '
        content: Also known as <b>Abijah.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Abijam Rules in Judah'
      title: Abijam Rules in Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  Abijam[[COMMENT(0)]] began to rule over Judah in the eighteenth
        year of Jeroboam\u2019s reign in Israel. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:1 '
        content: Also known as <b>Abijah.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He reigned in Jerusalem three years. His mother was Maacah, the granddaughter
        of Absalom.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Abishalom </b>(also in 15:10), a variant spelling of Absalom;
          compare 2 Chr 11:20.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'He committed the same sins as his father before him, and he was not
        faithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God, as his ancestor David
        had been. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But for David\u2019s sake, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God
        allowed his descendants to continue ruling, shining like a lamp, and he gave
        Abijam a son to rule after him in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "For David had done what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight and had obeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s commands throughout
        his life, except in the affair concerning Uriah the Hittite.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "There was war between Abijam and Jeroboam[[COMMENT(0)]] throughout
        Abijam\u2019s reign. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:6 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew and Greek manuscripts; most Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>between Rehoboam and Jeroboam.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The rest of the events in Abijam\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah. There was
        constant war between Abijam and Jeroboam. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: Asa Rules in Judah'
      title: Asa Rules in Judah
      number: 8
      content: 'When Abijam died, he was buried in the City of David. Then his son
        Asa became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Asa began to rule over Judah in the twentieth year of Jeroboam\u2019s
        reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He reigned in Jerusalem forty-one years. His grandmother[[COMMENT(0)]]
        was Maacah, the granddaughter of Absalom.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:10 '
        content: Or <b>The queen mother; </b>Hebrew reads <b>His mother </b>(also
          in 15:13); compare 15:2.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Asa did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, as his ancestor David had done. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'He banished the male and female shrine prostitutes from the land
        and got rid of all the idols[[COMMENT(0)]] his ancestors had made. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:12 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'He even deposed his grandmother Maacah from her position as queen
        mother because she had made an obscene Asherah pole. He cut down her obscene
        pole and burned it in the Kidron Valley. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Although the pagan shrines were not removed, Asa\u2019s heart remained
        completely faithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> throughout his life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'He brought into the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> the
        silver and gold and the various items that he and his father had dedicated.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'There was constant war between King Asa of Judah and King Baasha
        of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "King Baasha of Israel invaded Judah and fortified Ramah in order
        to prevent anyone from entering or leaving King Asa\u2019s territory in Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Asa responded by removing all the silver and gold that was left in
        the treasuries of the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and the royal
        palace. He sent it with some of his officials to Ben-hadad son of Tabrimmon,
        son of Hezion, the king of Aram, who was ruling in Damascus, along with this
        message:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CLet there be a treaty[[COMMENT(0)]] between you and me like
        the one between your father and my father. See, I am sending you a gift of
        silver and gold. Break your treaty with King Baasha of Israel so that he
        will leave me alone.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:19 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>There is a treaty.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Ben-hadad agreed to King Asa\u2019s request and sent the commanders
        of his army to attack the towns of Israel. They conquered the towns of Ijon,
        Dan, Abel-beth-maacah, and all Kinnereth, and all the land of Naphtali. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'As soon as Baasha of Israel heard what was happening, he abandoned
        his project of fortifying Ramah and withdrew to Tirzah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Then King Asa sent an order throughout Judah, requiring that everyone,
        without exception, help to carry away the building stones and timbers that
        Baasha had been using to fortify Ramah. Asa used these materials to fortify
        the town of Geba in Benjamin and the town of Mizpah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "The rest of the events in Asa\u2019s reign\u2014the extent of his
        power, everything he did, and the names of the cities he built\u2014are recorded
        in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah. In his old age his feet
        became diseased. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: Nadab Rules in Israel'
      title: Nadab Rules in Israel
      number: 24
      content: "When Asa died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David.Then
        Jehoshaphat, Asa\u2019s son, became the next king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Nadab son of Jeroboam began to rule over Israel in the second year
        of King Asa\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Israel two years. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "But he did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight and followed the example of his father, continuing the sins that Jeroboam
        had led Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Then Baasha son of Ahijah, from the tribe of Issachar, plotted against
        Nadab and assassinated him while he and the Israelite army were laying siege
        to the Philistine town of Gibbethon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Baasha killed Nadab in the third year of King Asa\u2019s reign in
        Judah, and he became the next king of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'He immediately slaughtered all the descendants of King Jeroboam,
        so that not one of the royal family was left, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had promised concerning Jeroboam by the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'This was done because Jeroboam had provoked the anger of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, by the sins he had committed and the sins he had led Israel
        to commit.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: Baasha Rules in Israel'
      title: Baasha Rules in Israel
      number: 31
      content: "The rest of the events in Nadab\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'There was constant war between King Asa of Judah and King Baasha
        of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Baasha son of Ahijah began to rule over all Israel in the third year
        of King Asa\u2019s reign in Judah. Baasha reigned in Tirzah twenty-four years. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "But he did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight and followed the example of Jeroboam, continuing the sins that Jeroboam
        had led Israel to commit."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: '  This message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was delivered
        to King Baasha by the prophet Jehu son of Hanani: '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CI lifted you out of the dust to make you ruler of my people
        Israel, but you have followed the evil example of Jeroboam. You have provoked
        my anger by causing my people Israel to sin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So now I will destroy you and your family, just as I destroyed the
        descendants of Jeroboam son of Nebat. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The members of Baasha\u2019s family who die in the city will be eaten
        by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by vultures.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The rest of the events in Baasha\u2019s reign and the extent of his
        power are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When Baasha died, he was buried in Tirzah. Then his son Elah became
        the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: Elah Rules in Israel'
      title: Elah Rules in Israel
      number: 7
      content: "The message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> against Baasha and
        his family came through the prophet Jehu son of Hanani. It was delivered
        because Baasha had done what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight (just as the family of Jeroboam had done), and also because Baasha
        had destroyed the family of Jeroboam. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anger was provoked by Baasha\u2019s sins.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Elah son of Baasha began to rule over Israel in the twenty-sixth
        year of King Asa\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in the city of Tirzah
        for two years.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then Zimri, who commanded half of the royal chariots, made plans
        to kill him. One day in Tirzah, Elah was getting drunk at the home of Arza,
        the supervisor of the palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Zimri walked in and struck him down and killed him. This happened
        in the twenty-seventh year of King Asa\u2019s reign in Judah. Then Zimri
        became the next king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Zimri immediately killed the entire royal family of Baasha, leaving
        him not even a single male child. He even destroyed distant relatives and
        friends. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So Zimri destroyed the dynasty of Baasha as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had promised through the prophet Jehu. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'This happened because of all the sins Baasha and his son Elah had
        committed, and because of the sins they led Israel to commit. They provoked
        the anger of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, with their
        worthless idols.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Zimri Rules in Israel'
      title: Zimri Rules in Israel
      number: 14
      content: "The rest of the events in Elah\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Zimri began to rule over Israel in the twenty-seventh year of King
        Asa\u2019s reign in Judah, but his reign in Tirzah lasted only seven days.
        The army of Israel was then attacking the Philistine town of Gibbethon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'When they heard that Zimri had committed treason and had assassinated
        the king, that very day they chose Omri, commander of the army, as the new
        king of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So Omri led the entire army of Israel up from Gibbethon to attack
        Tirzah, Israel\u2019s capital. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'When Zimri saw that the city had been taken, he went into the citadel
        of the palace and burned it down over himself and died in the flames. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "For he, too, had done what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He followed the example of Jeroboam in all the sins he had committed
        and led Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: Omri Rules in Israel'
      title: Omri Rules in Israel
      number: 20
      content: "The rest of the events in Zimri\u2019s reign and his conspiracy are
        recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'But now the people of Israel were split into two factions. Half the
        people tried to make Tibni son of Ginath their king, while the other half
        supported Omri. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "But Omri\u2019s supporters defeated the supporters of Tibni. So Tibni
        was killed, and Omri became the next king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Omri began to rule over Israel in the thirty-first year of King Asa\u2019s
        reign in Judah. He reigned twelve years in all, six of them in Tirzah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Then Omri bought the hill now known as Samaria from its owner, Shemer,
        for 150 pounds of silver.[[COMMENT(0)]] He built a city on it and called
        the city Samaria in honor of Shemer.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>for 2 talents </b>[68 kilograms] <b>of silver.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "But Omri did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, even more than any of the kings before him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'He followed the example of Jeroboam son of Nebat in all the sins
        he had committed and led Israel to commit. The people provoked the anger
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, with their worthless
        idols.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "The rest of the events in Omri\u2019s reign, the extent of his power,
        and everything he did are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings
        of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: Ahab Rules in Israel'
      title: Ahab Rules in Israel
      number: 28
      content: 'When Omri died, he was buried in Samaria. Then his son Ahab became
        the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Ahab son of Omri began to rule over Israel in the thirty-eighth year
        of King Asa\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria twenty-two years. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "But Ahab son of Omri did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, even more than any of the kings before him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'And as though it were not enough to follow the sinful example of
        Jeroboam, he married Jezebel, the daughter of King Ethbaal of the Sidonians,
        and he began to bow down in worship of Baal. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'First Ahab built a temple and an altar for Baal in Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Then he set up an Asherah pole. He did more to provoke the anger
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, than any of the other
        kings of Israel before him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: It was during his reign that Hiel, a man from Bethel, rebuilt Jericho.
        When he laid its foundations, it cost him the life of his oldest son, Abiram.
        And when he completed it and set up its gates, it cost him the life of his
        youngest son, Segub.[[COMMENT(0)]] This all happened according to the message
        from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> concerning Jericho spoken by Joshua
        son of Nun.
      comments:
      - number: '16:34 '
        content: An ancient Hebrew scribal tradition reads <b>He killed his oldest
          son when he laid its foundations, and he killed his youngest son when he
          set up its gates.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Elijah Fed by Ravens'
      title: Elijah Fed by Ravens
      number: 1
      content: "  Now Elijah, who was from Tishbe in Gilead, told King Ahab, \u201CAs
        surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, lives\u2014the
        God I serve\u2014there will be no dew or rain during the next few years until
        I give the word!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Elijah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CGo to the east and hide by Kerith Brook, near where it enters
        the Jordan River. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Drink from the brook and eat what the ravens bring you, for I have
        commanded them to bring you food.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'So Elijah did as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him and camped
        beside Kerith Brook, east of the Jordan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The ravens brought him bread and meat each morning and evening, and
        he drank from the brook. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: The Widow at Zarephath'
      title: The Widow at Zarephath
      number: 7
      content: 'But after a while the brook dried up, for there was no rainfall anywhere
        in the land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Elijah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CGo and live in the village of Zarephath, near the city of Sidon.
        I have instructed a widow there to feed you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So he went to Zarephath. As he arrived at the gates of the village,
        he saw a widow gathering sticks, and he asked her, \u201CWould you please
        bring me a little water in a cup?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "As she was going to get it, he called to her, \u201CBring me a bite
        of bread, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "But she said, \u201CI swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God that I don\u2019t have a single piece of bread in the house. And I have
        only a handful of flour left in the jar and a little cooking oil in the bottom
        of the jug. I was just gathering a few sticks to cook this last meal, and
        then my son and I will die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "But Elijah said to her, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid! Go ahead and
        do just what you\u2019ve said, but make a little bread for me first. Then
        use what\u2019s left to prepare a meal for yourself and your son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "For this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        says: There will always be flour and olive oil left in your containers until
        the time when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sends rain and the crops grow
        again!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So she did as Elijah said, and she and Elijah and her family continued
        to eat for many days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'There was always enough flour and olive oil left in the containers,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised through Elijah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Some time later the woman\u2019s son became sick. He grew worse and
        worse, and finally he died. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then she said to Elijah, \u201CO man of God, what have you done to
        me? Have you come here to point out my sins and kill my son?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But Elijah replied, \u201CGive me your son.\u201D And he took the
        child\u2019s body from her arms, carried him up the stairs to the room where
        he was staying, and laid the body on his bed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then Elijah cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CO
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God, why have you brought tragedy to this
        widow who has opened her home to me, causing her son to die?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "And he stretched himself out over the child three times and cried
        out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God, please let this child\u2019s life return to him.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> heard Elijah\u2019s prayer, and the
        life of the child returned, and he revived! "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then Elijah brought him down from the upper room and gave him to
        his mother. \u201CLook!\u201D he said. \u201CYour son is alive!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then the woman told Elijah, \u201CNow I know for sure that you are
        a man of God, and that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> truly speaks through
        you.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Contest on Mount Carmel'
      title: The Contest on Mount Carmel
      number: 1
      content: "  Later on, in the third year of the drought, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Elijah, \u201CGo and present yourself to King Ahab. Tell him that
        I will soon send rain!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So Elijah went to appear before Ahab.Meanwhile, the famine had become
        very severe in Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So Ahab summoned Obadiah, who was in charge of the palace. (Obadiah
        was a devoted follower of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Once when Jezebel had tried to kill all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        prophets, Obadiah had hidden 100 of them in two caves. He put fifty prophets
        in each cave and supplied them with food and water.) "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Ahab said to Obadiah, \u201CWe must check every spring and valley
        in the land to see if we can find enough grass to save at least some of my
        horses and mules.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So they divided the land between them. Ahab went one way by himself,
        and Obadiah went another way by himself.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "As Obadiah was walking along, he suddenly saw Elijah coming toward
        him. Obadiah recognized him at once and bowed low to the ground before him.
        \u201CIs it really you, my lord Elijah?\u201D he asked.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CYes, it is,\u201D Elijah replied. \u201CNow go and tell your
        master, \u2018Elijah is here.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201COh, sir,\u201D Obadiah protested, \u201Cwhat harm have I done
        to you that you are sending me to my death at the hands of Ahab? "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "For I swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God that the
        king has searched every nation and kingdom on earth from end to end to find
        you. And each time he was told, \u2018Elijah isn\u2019t here,\u2019 King
        Ahab forced the king of that nation to swear to the truth of his claim. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "And now you say, \u2018Go and tell your master, \u201CElijah is here.\u201D\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But as soon as I leave you, the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will carry you away to who knows where. When Ahab comes and cannot find you,
        he will kill me. Yet I have been a true servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        all my life. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Has no one told you, my lord, about the time when Jezebel was trying
        to kill the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s prophets? I hid 100 of them
        in two caves and supplied them with food and water. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "And now you say, \u2018Go and tell your master, \u201CElijah is here.\u201D\u2019
        Sir, if I do that, Ahab will certainly kill me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "But Elijah said, \u201CI swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        Almighty, in whose presence I stand, that I will present myself to Ahab this
        very day.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So Obadiah went to tell Ahab that Elijah had come, and Ahab went
        out to meet Elijah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "When Ahab saw him, he exclaimed, \u201CSo, is it really you, you
        troublemaker of Israel?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CI have made no trouble for Israel,\u201D Elijah replied. \u201CYou
        and your family are the troublemakers, for you have refused to obey the commands
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and have worshiped the images of Baal
        instead. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Now summon all Israel to join me at Mount Carmel, along with the
        450 prophets of Baal and the 400 prophets of Asherah who are supported by
        Jezebel.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:19 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>who eat at Jezebel\u2019s table.</b>"
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'So Ahab summoned all the people of Israel and the prophets to Mount
        Carmel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Elijah stood in front of them and said, \u201CHow much longer
        will you waver, hobbling between two opinions? If the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is God, follow him! But if Baal is God, then follow him!\u201D But the people
        were completely silent.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then Elijah said to them, \u201CI am the only prophet of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        who is left, but Baal has 450 prophets. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Now bring two bulls. The prophets of Baal may choose whichever one
        they wish and cut it into pieces and lay it on the wood of their altar, but
        without setting fire to it. I will prepare the other bull and lay it on the
        wood on the altar, but not set fire to it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then call on the name of your god, and I will call on the name of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. The god who answers by setting fire to the
        wood is the true God!\u201D And all the people agreed.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then Elijah said to the prophets of Baal, \u201CYou go first, for
        there are many of you. Choose one of the bulls, and prepare it and call on
        the name of your god. But do not set fire to the wood.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "So they prepared one of the bulls and placed it on the altar. Then
        they called on the name of Baal from morning until noontime, shouting, \u201CO
        Baal, answer us!\u201D But there was no reply of any kind. Then they danced,
        hobbling around the altar they had made.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "About noontime Elijah began mocking them. \u201CYou\u2019ll have
        to shout louder,\u201D he scoffed, \u201Cfor surely he is a god! Perhaps
        he is daydreaming, or is relieving himself.[[COMMENT(0)]] Or maybe he is
        away on a trip, or is asleep and needs to be wakened!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:27 '
        content: Or <b>is busy somewhere else, </b>or <b>is engaged in business.</b>
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'So they shouted louder, and following their normal custom, they cut
        themselves with knives and swords until the blood gushed out. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'They raved all afternoon until the time of the evening sacrifice,
        but still there was no sound, no reply, no response.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Then Elijah called to the people, \u201CCome over here!\u201D They
        all crowded around him as he repaired the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that had been torn down. "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: He took twelve stones, one to represent each of the tribes of Israel,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '18:31 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>each of the tribes of the sons of Jacob to whom the <span
          class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span> had said, \u201CYour name
          will be Israel.\u201D</b>"
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'and he used the stones to rebuild the altar in the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then he dug a trench around the altar large enough to hold about three gallons.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 seahs </b>[14.6 liters] <b>of seed.</b>
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "He piled wood on the altar, cut the bull into pieces, and laid the
        pieces on the wood.[[COMMENT(0)]]Then he said, \u201CFill four large jars
        with water, and pour the water over the offering and the wood.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:33 '
        content: Verse 18:34 in the Hebrew text begins here.
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "After they had done this, he said, \u201CDo the same thing again!\u201D
        And when they were finished, he said, \u201CNow do it a third time!\u201D
        So they did as he said, "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'and the water ran around the altar and even filled the trench.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "At the usual time for offering the evening sacrifice, Elijah the
        prophet walked up to the altar and prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob,[[COMMENT(0)]] prove today that you are
        God in Israel and that I am your servant. Prove that I have done all this
        at your command. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:36 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>and Israel. </b>The names \u201CJacob\u201D and \u201CIsrael\u201D
          are often interchanged throughout the Old Testament, referring sometimes
          to the individual patriarch and sometimes to the nation."
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, answer me! Answer me so these people
        will know that you, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, are God and that you have
        brought them back to yourself.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Immediately the fire of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> flashed down
        from heaven and burned up the young bull, the wood, the stones, and the dust.
        It even licked up all the water in the trench! '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "And when all the people saw it, they fell face down on the ground
        and cried out, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014he is God! Yes,
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is God!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: Elijah Prays for Rain'
      title: Elijah Prays for Rain
      number: 40
      content: "Then Elijah commanded, \u201CSeize all the prophets of Baal. Don\u2019t
        let a single one escape!\u201D So the people seized them all, and Elijah
        took them down to the Kishon Valley and killed them there.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Then Elijah said to Ahab, \u201CGo get something to eat and drink,
        for I hear a mighty rainstorm coming!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'So Ahab went to eat and drink. But Elijah climbed to the top of Mount
        Carmel and bowed low to the ground and prayed with his face between his knees.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Then he said to his servant, \u201CGo and look out toward the sea.\u201DThe
        servant went and looked, then returned to Elijah and said, \u201CI didn\u2019t
        see anything.\u201DSeven times Elijah told him to go and look. "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "Finally the seventh time, his servant told him, \u201CI saw a little
        cloud about the size of a man\u2019s hand rising from the sea.\u201DThen
        Elijah shouted, \u201CHurry to Ahab and tell him, \u2018Climb into your chariot
        and go back home. If you don\u2019t hurry, the rain will stop you!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'And soon the sky was black with clouds. A heavy wind brought a terrific
        rainstorm, and Ahab left quickly for Jezreel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave special strength to Elijah.
        He tucked his cloak into his belt[[COMMENT(0)]] and ran ahead of Ahab\u2019s
        chariot all the way to the entrance of Jezreel."
      comments:
      - number: '18:46 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He bound up his loins.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Elijah Flees to Sinai'
      title: Elijah Flees to Sinai
      number: 1
      content: '  When Ahab got home, he told Jezebel everything Elijah had done,
        including the way he had killed all the prophets of Baal. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So Jezebel sent this message to Elijah: \u201CMay the gods strike
        me and even kill me if by this time tomorrow I have not killed you just as
        you killed them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Elijah was afraid and fled for his life. He went to Beersheba, a
        town in Judah, and he left his servant there. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then he went on alone into the wilderness, traveling all day. He
        sat down under a solitary broom tree and prayed that he might die. \u201CI
        have had enough, <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D he said. \u201CTake my
        life, for I am no better than my ancestors who have already died.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then he lay down and slept under the broom tree. But as he was sleeping,
        an angel touched him and told him, \u201CGet up and eat!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He looked around and there beside his head was some bread baked on
        hot stones and a jar of water! So he ate and drank and lay down again.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came again and
        touched him and said, \u201CGet up and eat some more, or the journey ahead
        will be too much for you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So he got up and ate and drank, and the food gave him enough strength
        to travel forty days and forty nights to Mount Sinai,[[COMMENT(0)]] the mountain
        of God. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - name: '9: The  Speaks to Elijah'
      title: The  Speaks to Elijah
      number: 9
      content: "There he came to a cave, where he spent the night.<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>But
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to him, \u201CWhat are you doing here,
        Elijah?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Elijah replied, \u201CI have zealously served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God Almighty. But the people of Israel have broken their covenant with you,
        torn down your altars, and killed every one of your prophets. I am the only
        one left, and now they are trying to kill me, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CGo out and stand before me on the mountain,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him. And as Elijah stood there, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> passed
        by, and a mighty windstorm hit the mountain. It was such a terrible blast
        that the rocks were torn loose, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was not
        in the wind. After the wind there was an earthquake, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was not in the earthquake. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'And after the earthquake there was a fire, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was not in the fire. And after the fire there was the sound of a gentle whisper. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When Elijah heard it, he wrapped his face in his cloak and went out
        and stood at the entrance of the cave.And a voice said, \u201CWhat are you
        doing here, Elijah?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "He replied again, \u201CI have zealously served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God Almighty. But the people of Israel have broken their covenant with you,
        torn down your altars, and killed every one of your prophets. I am the only
        one left, and now they are trying to kill me, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CGo back the
        same way you came, and travel to the wilderness of Damascus. When you arrive
        there, anoint Hazael to be king of Aram. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then anoint Jehu grandson of Nimshi[[COMMENT(0)]] to be king of Israel,
        and anoint Elisha son of Shaphat from the town of Abel-meholah to replace
        you as my prophet. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>descendant of Nimshi; </b>compare 2 Kgs 9:2, 14.
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Anyone who escapes from Hazael will be killed by Jehu, and those
        who escape Jehu will be killed by Elisha! '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: The Call of Elisha'
      title: The Call of Elisha
      number: 18
      content: "Yet I will preserve 7,000 others in Israel who have never bowed down
        to Baal or kissed him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'So Elijah went and found Elisha son of Shaphat plowing a field. There
        were twelve teams of oxen in the field, and Elisha was plowing with the twelfth
        team. Elijah went over to him and threw his cloak across his shoulders and
        then walked away. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Elisha left the oxen standing there, ran after Elijah, and said to
        him, \u201CFirst let me go and kiss my father and mother good-bye, and then
        I will go with you!\u201DElijah replied, \u201CGo on back, but think about
        what I have done to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: So Elisha returned to his oxen and slaughtered them. He used the wood
        from the plow to build a fire to roast their flesh. He passed around the
        meat to the townspeople, and they all ate. Then he went with Elijah as his
        assistant.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ben-Hadad Attacks Samaria'
      title: Ben-Hadad Attacks Samaria
      number: 1
      content: '  About that time King Ben-hadad of Aram mobilized his army, supported
        by the chariots and horses of thirty-two allied kings. They went to besiege
        Samaria, the capital of Israel, and launched attacks against it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Ben-hadad sent messengers into the city to relay this message to
        King Ahab of Israel: \u201CThis is what Ben-hadad says: "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u2018Your silver and gold are mine, and so are your wives and the
        best of your children!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CAll right, my lord the king,\u201D Israel\u2019s king replied.
        \u201CAll that I have is yours!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Soon Ben-hadad\u2019s messengers returned again and said, \u201CThis
        is what Ben-hadad says: \u2018I have already demanded that you give me your
        silver, gold, wives, and children. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But about this time tomorrow I will send my officials to search your
        palace and the homes of your officials. They will take away everything you
        consider valuable!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Ahab summoned all the elders of the land and said to them, \u201CLook
        how this man is stirring up trouble! I already agreed with his demand that
        I give him my wives and children and silver and gold.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t give in to any more demands,\u201D all the elders
        and the people advised.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "So Ahab told the messengers from Ben-hadad, \u201CSay this to my
        lord the king: \u2018I will give you everything you asked for the first time,
        but I cannot accept this last demand of yours.\u2019\u201D So the messengers
        returned to Ben-hadad with that response.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then Ben-hadad sent this message to Ahab: \u201CMay the gods strike
        me and even kill me if there remains enough dust from Samaria to provide
        even a handful for each of my soldiers.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The king of Israel sent back this answer: \u201CA warrior putting
        on his sword for battle should not boast like a warrior who has already won.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: "12: Ahab\u2019s Victory over Ben-Hadad"
      title: "Ahab\u2019s Victory over Ben-Hadad"
      number: 12
      content: "Ahab\u2019s reply reached Ben-hadad and the other kings as they were
        drinking in their tents.[[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CPrepare to attack!\u201D Ben-hadad
        commanded his officers. So they prepared to attack the city.  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:12 '
        content: Or <b>in Succoth; </b>also in 20:16.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then a certain prophet came to see King Ahab of Israel and told him,
        \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Do you see all these
        enemy forces? Today I will hand them all over to you. Then you will know
        that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Ahab asked, \u201CHow will he do it?\u201DAnd the prophet replied,
        \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: The troops of the
        provincial commanders will do it.\u201D\u201CShould we attack first?\u201D
        Ahab asked.\u201CYes,\u201D the prophet answered.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So Ahab mustered the troops of the 232 provincial commanders. Then
        he called out the rest of the army of Israel, some 7,000 men. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'About noontime, as Ben-hadad and the thirty-two allied kings were
        still in their tents drinking themselves into a stupor, '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "the troops of the provincial commanders marched out of the city as
        the first contingent.As they approached, Ben-hadad\u2019s scouts reported
        to him, \u201CSome troops are coming from Samaria.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CTake them alive,\u201D Ben-hadad commanded, \u201Cwhether they
        have come for peace or for war.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But Ahab\u2019s provincial commanders and the entire army had now
        come out to fight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Each Israelite soldier killed his Aramean opponent, and suddenly
        the entire Aramean army panicked and fled. The Israelites chased them, but
        King Ben-hadad and a few of his charioteers escaped on horses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'However, the king of Israel destroyed the other horses and chariots
        and slaughtered the Arameans.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "22: Ben-Hadad\u2019s Second Attack"
      title: "Ben-Hadad\u2019s Second Attack"
      number: 22
      content: "Afterward the prophet said to King Ahab, \u201CGet ready for another
        attack. Begin making plans now, for the king of Aram will come back next
        spring.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at the turn of the year; </b>similarly in 20:26. The first
          day of the year in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March
          or April.
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "After their defeat, Ben-hadad\u2019s officers said to him, \u201CThe
        Israelite gods are gods of the hills; that is why they won. But we can beat
        them easily on the plains. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Only this time replace the kings with field commanders! '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Recruit another army like the one you lost. Give us the same number
        of horses, chariots, and men, and we will fight against them on the plains.
        There\u2019s no doubt that we will beat them.\u201D So King Ben-hadad did
        as they suggested.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'The following spring he called up the Aramean army and marched out
        against Israel, this time at Aphek. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Israel then mustered its army, set up supply lines, and marched out
        for battle. But the Israelite army looked like two little flocks of goats
        in comparison to the vast Aramean forces that filled the countryside!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Then the man of God went to the king of Israel and said, \u201CThis
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: The Arameans have said, \u2018The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is a god of the hills and not of the plains.\u2019
        So I will defeat this vast army for you. Then you will know that I am the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'The two armies camped opposite each other for seven days, and on
        the seventh day the battle began. The Israelites killed 100,000 Aramean foot
        soldiers in one day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'The rest fled into the town of Aphek, but the wall fell on them and
        killed another 27,000. Ben-hadad fled into the town and hid in a secret room.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Ben-hadad\u2019s officers said to him, \u201CSir, we have heard that
        the kings of Israel are merciful. So let\u2019s humble ourselves by wearing
        burlap around our waists and putting ropes on our heads, and surrender to
        the king of Israel. Then perhaps he will let you live.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "So they put on burlap and ropes, and they went to the king of Israel
        and begged, \u201CYour servant Ben-hadad says, \u2018Please let me live!\u2019\u201DThe
        king of Israel responded, \u201CIs he still alive? He is my brother!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "The men took this as a good sign and quickly picked up on his words.
        \u201CYes,\u201D they said, \u201Cyour brother Ben-hadad!\u201D\u201CGo and
        get him,\u201D the king of Israel told them. And when Ben-hadad arrived,
        Ahab invited him up into his chariot.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: A Prophet Condemns Ahab'
      title: A Prophet Condemns Ahab
      number: 34
      content: "Ben-hadad told him, \u201CI will give back the towns my father took
        from your father, and you may establish places of trade in Damascus, as my
        father did in Samaria.\u201DThen Ahab said, \u201CI will release you under
        these conditions.\u201D So they made a new treaty, and Ben-hadad was set
        free.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Meanwhile, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> instructed one of the
        group of prophets to say to another man, \u201CHit me!\u201D But the man
        refused to hit the prophet. "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Then the prophet told him, \u201CBecause you have not obeyed the
        voice of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, a lion will kill you as soon as
        you leave me.\u201D And when he had gone, a lion did attack and kill him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Then the prophet turned to another man and said, \u201CHit me!\u201D
        So he struck the prophet and wounded him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'The prophet placed a bandage over his eyes to disguise himself and
        then waited beside the road for the king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "As the king passed by, the prophet called out to him, \u201CSir,
        I was in the thick of battle, and suddenly a man brought me a prisoner. He
        said, \u2018Guard this man; if for any reason he gets away, you will either
        die or pay a fine of seventy-five pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver!\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: '20:39 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 talent </b>[34 kilograms].
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "But while I was busy doing something else, the prisoner disappeared!\u201D\u201CWell,
        it\u2019s your own fault,\u201D the king replied. \u201CYou have brought
        the judgment on yourself.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'Then the prophet quickly pulled the bandage from his eyes, and the
        king of Israel recognized him as one of the prophets. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "The prophet said to him, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Because you have spared the man I said must be destroyed,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        now you must die in his place, and your people will die instead of his people.\u201D
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '20:42 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: So the king of Israel went home to Samaria angry and sullen.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Naboth\u2019s Vineyard"
      title: "Naboth\u2019s Vineyard"
      number: 1
      content: '  Now there was a man named Naboth, from Jezreel, who owned a vineyard
        in Jezreel beside the palace of King Ahab of Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "One day Ahab said to Naboth, \u201CSince your vineyard is so convenient
        to my palace, I would like to buy it to use as a vegetable garden. I will
        give you a better vineyard in exchange, or if you prefer, I will pay you
        for it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Naboth replied, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> forbid
        that I should give you the inheritance that was passed down by my ancestors.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So Ahab went home angry and sullen because of Naboth\u2019s answer.
        The king went to bed with his face to the wall and refused to eat!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CWhat\u2019s the matter?\u201D his wife Jezebel asked him. \u201CWhat\u2019s
        made you so upset that you\u2019re not eating?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CI asked Naboth to sell me his vineyard or trade it, but he
        refused!\u201D Ahab told her.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CAre you the king of Israel or not?\u201D Jezebel demanded.
        \u201CGet up and eat something, and don\u2019t worry about it. I\u2019ll
        get you Naboth\u2019s vineyard!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "So she wrote letters in Ahab\u2019s name, sealed them with his seal,
        and sent them to the elders and other leaders of the town where Naboth lived. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "In her letters she commanded: \u201CCall the citizens together for
        a time of fasting, and give Naboth a place of honor. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And then seat two scoundrels across from him who will accuse him
        of cursing God and the king. Then take him out and stone him to death.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'So the elders and other town leaders followed the instructions Jezebel
        had written in the letters. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'They called for a fast and put Naboth at a prominent place before
        the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then the two scoundrels came and sat down across from him. And they
        accused Naboth before all the people, saying, \u201CHe cursed God and the
        king.\u201D So he was dragged outside the town and stoned to death. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The town leaders then sent word to Jezebel, \u201CNaboth has been
        stoned to death.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When Jezebel heard the news, she said to Ahab, \u201CYou know the
        vineyard Naboth wouldn\u2019t sell you? Well, you can have it now! He\u2019s
        dead!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So Ahab immediately went down to the vineyard of Naboth to claim
        it.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Elijah,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Elijah the Tishbite; </b>also in 21:28.
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CGo down to meet King Ahab of Israel, who rules in Samaria.
        He will be at Naboth\u2019s vineyard in Jezreel, claiming it for himself. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Give him this message: \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Wasn\u2019t it enough that you killed Naboth? Must you rob him, too?
        Because you have done this, dogs will lick your blood at the very place where
        they licked the blood of Naboth!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CSo, my enemy, you have found me!\u201D Ahab exclaimed to Elijah.\u201CYes,\u201D
        Elijah answered, \u201CI have come because you have sold yourself to what
        is evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "So now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        \u2018I will bring disaster on you and consume you. I will destroy every
        one of your male descendants, slave and free alike, anywhere in Israel! </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '21:21 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew lacks <b>So now the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>
          says.</b>
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "I am going to destroy your family as I did the family of Jeroboam
        son of Nebat and the family of Baasha son of Ahijah, for you have made me
        very angry and have led Israel into sin.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CAnd regarding Jezebel, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says,
        \u2018Dogs will eat Jezebel\u2019s body at the plot of land in Jezreel.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:23 '
        content: As in several Hebrew manuscripts, Syriac, and Latin Vulgate (see
          also 2 Kgs 9:26, 36); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>at the city wall.</b>
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CThe members of Ahab\u2019s family who die in the city will
        be eaten by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by vultures.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "(No one else so completely sold himself to what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight as Ahab did under the influence of his wife Jezebel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "His worst outrage was worshiping idols[[COMMENT(0)]] just as the
        Amorites had done\u2014the people whom the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        driven out from the land ahead of the Israelites.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:26 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'But when Ahab heard this message, he tore his clothing, dressed in
        burlap, and fasted. He even slept in burlap and went about in deep mourning.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Then another message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came to
        Elijah: '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CDo you see how Ahab has humbled himself before me? Because
        he has done this, I will not do what I promised during his lifetime. It will
        happen to his sons; I will destroy his dynasty.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jehoshaphat and Ahab'
      title: Jehoshaphat and Ahab
      number: 1
      content: '  For three years there was no war between Aram and Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then during the third year, King Jehoshaphat of Judah went to visit
        King Ahab of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "During the visit, the king of Israel said to his officials, \u201CDo
        you realize that the town of Ramoth-gilead belongs to us? And yet we\u2019ve
        done nothing to recapture it from the king of Aram!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then he turned to Jehoshaphat and asked, \u201CWill you join me in
        battle to recover Ramoth-gilead?\u201DJehoshaphat replied to the king of
        Israel, \u201CWhy, of course! You and I are as one. My troops are your troops,
        and my horses are your horses.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then Jehoshaphat added, \u201CBut first let\u2019s find out what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So the king of Israel summoned the prophets, about 400 of them, and
        asked them, \u201CShould I go to war against Ramoth-gilead, or should I hold
        back?\u201DThey all replied, \u201CYes, go right ahead! The Lord will give
        the king victory.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But Jehoshaphat asked, \u201CIs there not also a prophet of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        here? We should ask him the same question.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The king of Israel replied to Jehoshaphat, \u201CThere is one more
        man who could consult the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for us, but I hate
        him. He never prophesies anything but trouble for me! His name is Micaiah
        son of Imlah.\u201DJehoshaphat replied, \u201CThat\u2019s not the way a king
        should talk! Let\u2019s hear what he has to say.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: Micaiah Prophesies against Ahab'
      title: Micaiah Prophesies against Ahab
      number: 9
      content: "So the king of Israel called one of his officials and said, \u201CQuick!
        Bring Micaiah son of Imlah.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah, dressed in their
        royal robes, were sitting on thrones at the threshing floor near the gate
        of Samaria. All of Ahab\u2019s prophets were prophesying there in front of
        them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "One of them, Zedekiah son of Kenaanah, made some iron horns and proclaimed,
        \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: With these horns
        you will gore the Arameans to death!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "All the other prophets agreed. \u201CYes,\u201D they said, \u201Cgo
        up to Ramoth-gilead and be victorious, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will give the king victory!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Meanwhile, the messenger who went to get Micaiah said to him, \u201CLook,
        all the prophets are promising victory for the king. Be sure that you agree
        with them and promise success.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But Micaiah replied, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives, I will say only what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> tells me to say.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When Micaiah arrived before the king, Ahab asked him, \u201CMicaiah,
        should we go to war against Ramoth-gilead, or should we hold back?\u201DMicaiah
        replied sarcastically, \u201CYes, go up and be victorious, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will give the king victory!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But the king replied sharply, \u201CHow many times must I demand
        that you speak only the truth to me when you speak for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Micaiah told him, \u201CIn a vision I saw all Israel scattered
        on the mountains, like sheep without a shepherd. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said, \u2018Their master has been killed.[[COMMENT(0)]] Send them home in
        peace.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>These people have no master.</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CDidn\u2019t I tell you?\u201D the king of Israel exclaimed
        to Jehoshaphat. \u201CHe never prophesies anything but trouble for me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then Micaiah continued, \u201CListen to what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says! I saw the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sitting on his throne with all
        the armies of heaven around him, on his right and on his left. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u2018Who can entice Ahab
        to go into battle against Ramoth-gilead so he can be killed?\u2019\u201CThere
        were many suggestions, "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "and finally a spirit approached the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        said, \u2018I can do it!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201C\u2018How will you do this?\u2019 the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        asked.\u201CAnd the spirit replied, \u2018I will go out and inspire all of
        Ahab\u2019s prophets to speak lies.\u2019\u201C\u2018You will succeed,\u2019
        said the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. \u2018Go ahead and do it.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CSo you see, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has put a lying
        spirit in the mouths of all your prophets. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has pronounced your doom.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Zedekiah son of Kenaanah walked up to Micaiah and slapped him
        across the face. \u201CSince when did the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        leave me to speak to you?\u201D he demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "And Micaiah replied, \u201CYou will find out soon enough when you
        are trying to hide in some secret room!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CArrest him!\u201D the king of Israel ordered. \u201CTake him
        back to Amon, the governor of the city, and to my son Joash. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Give them this order from the king: \u2018Put this man in prison,
        and feed him nothing but bread and water until I return safely from the battle!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: The Death of Ahab'
      title: The Death of Ahab
      number: 28
      content: "But Micaiah replied, \u201CIf you return safely, it will mean that
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has not spoken through me!\u201D Then he
        added to those standing around, \u201CEveryone mark my words!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah led their armies
        against Ramoth-gilead. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "The king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, \u201CAs we go into battle,
        I will disguise myself so no one will recognize me, but you wear your royal
        robes.\u201D So the king of Israel disguised himself, and they went into
        battle.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Meanwhile, the king of Aram had issued these orders to his thirty-two
        chariot commanders: \u201CAttack only the king of Israel. Don\u2019t bother
        with anyone else!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "So when the Aramean chariot commanders saw Jehoshaphat in his royal
        robes, they went after him. \u201CThere is the king of Israel!\u201D they
        shouted. But when Jehoshaphat called out, "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'the chariot commanders realized he was not the king of Israel, and
        they stopped chasing him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "An Aramean soldier, however, randomly shot an arrow at the Israelite
        troops and hit the king of Israel between the joints of his armor. \u201CTurn
        the horses[[COMMENT(0)]] and get me out of here!\u201D Ahab groaned to the
        driver of his chariot. \u201CI\u2019m badly wounded!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:34 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Turn your hand.</b>
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'The battle raged all that day, and the king remained propped up in
        his chariot facing the Arameans. The blood from his wound ran down to the
        floor of his chariot, and as evening arrived he died. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Just as the sun was setting, the cry ran through his troops: \u201CWe\u2019re
        done for! Run for your lives!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'So the king died, and his body was taken to Samaria and buried there. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Then his chariot was washed beside the pool of Samaria, and dogs
        came and licked his blood at the place where the prostitutes bathed,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:38 '
        content: Or <b>his blood, and the prostitutes bathed [in it]; </b>or <b>his
          blood, and they washed his armor.</b>
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "The rest of the events in Ahab\u2019s reign and everything he did,
        including the story of the ivory palace and the towns he built, are recorded
        in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: Jehoshaphat Rules in Judah'
      title: Jehoshaphat Rules in Judah
      number: 40
      content: 'So Ahab died, and his son Ahaziah became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Jehoshaphat son of Asa began to rule over Judah in the fourth year
        of King Ahab\u2019s reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'Jehoshaphat was thirty-five years old when he became king, and he
        reigned in Jerusalem twenty-five years. His mother was Azubah, the daughter
        of Shilhi.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Jehoshaphat was a good king, following the example of his father,
        Asa. He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]During his reign, however, he failed to remove all the pagan
        shrines, and the people still offered sacrifices and burned incense there. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:43 '
        content: Verses 22:43b-53 are numbered 22:44-54 in Hebrew text.
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'Jehoshaphat also made peace with the king of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoshaphat\u2019s reign, the extent of
        his power, and the wars he waged are recorded in The Book of the History
        of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'He banished from the land the rest of the male and female shrine
        prostitutes, who still continued their practices from the days of his father,
        Asa.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: '(There was no king in Edom at that time, only a deputy.)  '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Jehoshaphat also built a fleet of trading ships[[COMMENT(0)]] to
        sail to Ophir for gold. But the ships never set sail, for they met with disaster
        in their home port of Ezion-geber. '
      comments:
      - number: '22:48 '
        content: Hebrew <b>fleet of ships of Tarshish.</b>
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "At one time Ahaziah son of Ahab had proposed to Jehoshaphat, \u201CLet
        my men sail with your men in the ships.\u201D But Jehoshaphat refused the
        request.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '50: Ahaziah Rules in Israel'
      title: Ahaziah Rules in Israel
      number: 50
      content: 'When Jehoshaphat died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City
        of David. Then his son Jehoram became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "Ahaziah son of Ahab began to rule over Israel in the seventeenth
        year of King Jehoshaphat\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria two
        years. "
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "But he did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, following the example of his father and mother and the example of
        Jeroboam son of Nebat, who had led Israel to sin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: He served Baal and worshiped him, provoking the anger of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, just as his father had done.
      comments: []
